{"title_page": "Philippine adobo", "text_new": "{{short description|Filipino cooking process}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Philippine adobo\n| image            = Chicken adobo.jpg\n| caption          = Chicken ''adobo''\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Philippines]]\n| region           = \n| national_cuisine = [[Filipino cuisine]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Main course]]\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Meat]] ([[beef]], [[chicken]], [[pork]]), [[seafood]], or vegetables; [[soy sauce]], [[vinegar]], [[cooking oil]], [[garlic]], [[black pepper]]corn, [[bay leaf]]\n| variations       = Some sugar for sweet-salty taste\n| calories         = \n*Chicken: 107 [[Calorie|kcal]]\n*Pork: 342 [[Calorie|kcal]]\n*Beef: 349 \n| calories_ref     =<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfitnesspal.com/food/calories/generic-filipino-pork-adobo-325988545|title=Calories in Filipino Pork Adobo - Calories and Nutrition Facts - MyFitnessPal.com|website=www.myfitnesspal.com}})</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fatsecret.com/Diary.aspx?pa=fjrd&rid=255665|title=Calories in Beef Adobo and Nutrition Facts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fatsecret.com/calories-nutrition/generic/chicken-adobo|title=Calories in Chicken Adobo and Nutrition Facts|website=www.fatsecret.com}}</ref>\n| other            = \n| similar_dish     = [[paksiw]], [[kinilaw]]\n}}\n\n'''Philippine ''adobo''''' (from [[Spanish language|Spanish]] ''adobar'': \"[[marination|marinade]],\" \"sauce\" or \"seasoning\") is a popular Filipino dish and cooking process in [[Philippine cuisine]] that involves [[meat]], [[seafood]], or [[Vegetable|vegetables]] marinated in [[vinegar]], [[soy sauce]], [[garlic]], and [[Black pepper|black peppercorns]], which is browned in [[Cooking oil|oil]], and simmered in the marinade. It has occasionally been considered the unofficial national dish in the [[Philippines]].<ref name=\"dewitt\">{{cite book|author=DeWitt, Dave |title =1,001 Best Hot and Spicy Recipes|publisher =[[Agate Publishing]]|year =2010|page=428|isbn = 9781572841130|url =https://books.google.com/?id=sNLKs8LO35kC&lpg=PA428&dq=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&pg=PA428#v=onepage&q=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Pangilinan, Jr. | first = Leon | title = In Focus: 9 Facts You May Not Know About Philippine National Symbols | url=http://ncca.gov.ph/about-culture-and-arts/in-focus/9-facts-you-may-not-know-about-philippine-national-symbols/ | date = 3 October 2014 | accessdate = 8 January 2019 | publisher = [[National Commission for Culture and the Arts]]}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe cooking method for the Philippine ''adobo'' is indigenous to the [[Philippines]]. [[History of the Philippines (900\u20131521)|Pre-colonial]] Filipinos often cooked or prepared their food with [[vinegar]] and salt to keep them fresh longer in the [[tropical]] climate of the Philippines. Vinegar, in particular, is one of the most important ingredients in Filipino cuisine, with four main traditional types: [[coconut vinegar]], [[cane vinegar]], [[nipa palm vinegar]], and [[kaong palm vinegar]], all of which are linked to traditional [[Alcoholic drink|alcohol]] [[fermentation]].<ref name=\"hosking\"/><ref name=\"Ponseca\"/>\n[[File:Chicken Adobo over rice.jpg|thumb|left|Chicken ''adobo'' on white [[rice]]]]\nThere are four main traditional cooking methods using vinegar that are still widely prevalent in the Philippines today: ''[[kinilaw]]'' (raw seafood in vinegar and spices), ''[[paksiw]]'' (a broth of meat with vinegar and spices), ''[[sangkutsa]]'' (pre-cooking meat by [[braising]] them in vinegar and spices), and finally ''adobo'' (a stew of vinegar, garlic, salt/soy sauce, and other spices).<ref name=\"asianjournal.wordpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://asianjournal.wordpress.com/2008/07/14/adobo-a-history-of-the-countrys-national-dish/|title=ADOBO: A History of the Country's National Dish|date=14 July 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"rodell\"/><ref name=\"estrella\"/><ref name=\"hosking\"/> It is believed that ''paksiw'', ''sangkutsa'', and ''adobo'' were all derivations of ''kinilaw''. They are also related to cooking techniques like ''[[sinigang]]'' and ''[[pinangat na isda]]'' that also have a sour broth, albeit using native fruits like [[calamansi]], [[tamarind]], unripe [[mango]]es, [[bilimbi]], [[Sandoricum koetjape|santol]], and [[carambola|star fruit]] instead of vinegar.<ref name=\"Ponseca\">{{cite book |last1=Ponseca |first1=Nicole |last2=Trinidad |first2=Miguel |title=I Am a Filipino: And This Is How We Cook |date=2018 |publisher=Artisan Books |isbn=9781579658823 |url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=63BMDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Spanish Empire]] colonized the [[Philippines]] in the late 16th century and early 17th century, they encountered the ''adobo'' cooking process. It was first recorded in the dictionary ''[[Vocabulario de la lengua tagala]]'' (1613) compiled by the Spanish [[Franciscan]] missionary [[Pedro de San Buenaventura]]. He referred to it as ''adobo de los naturales'' (\"''[[adobo]]'' of the native peoples\").<ref name=\"rodell\"/><ref name=\"estrella\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pepper.ph/the-history-of-adobo/|title=Adobo: The History of A National Favorite|author= Estrella, Serna|date=June 22, 2013|publisher=Pepper.ph|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"hosking\">{{cite book|author=Lim-Castillo, Pia|editor =Hosking, Richard|title =Authenticity in the Kitchen|chapter =Traditional Philippine Vinegars and their Role in Shaping the Culinary Culture|publisher =Prospect Books|series =Proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery 2005|year =2006|page=296&ndash;298|isbn =9781903018477|chapter-url =https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=HflTVd898PAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> \n\nThe Spanish also applied the term ''adobo'' to any native dish that was marinated before consumption. In the 1794 edition of ''Vocabulario de la lengua Tagala'', it was applied to ''quilau\u00ecn'' (''[[kinilaw]]'') a related but different dish which also primarily uses vinegar.<ref name=\"vlt\">{{cite book|author=Domingo de los Santos\n|editor =|title =Vocabulario de la lengua Tagala, primera y segunda parte: en la primera, se pone primero el Castellano, y despues el Tagalo : y en la segunda al contrario, que son las rayzes simples con sus accentos|chapter =|publisher =N.S. de Loreto |series =|year =1794|page=42|isbn =|quote=Adobo. Quilau\u00ecn. (pc) toman s\u00e0l vinagre, y ch\u00edle, y lo echan en la carne, pescado, \u00f2 tripas de venado; y asi medio crudo lo comen . . . Este mismo genero de adobo sirve para las yervas como ensalada.\n|url =https://books.google.com/?id=XitOAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA42&dq=vocabulario+de+la+lengua+tagala+adobo#v=onepage&q=vocabulario%20de%20la%20lengua%20tagala%20adobo&f=false}}</ref> In ''Vocabulario de la lengua Bisaya'' (1711), the term ''guinamus'' (verb form: ''gamus'') was used to refer to any kind of marinades (''adobo''), from fish to pork. Other terms for precolonial ''adobo''-like dishes among the Visayan peoples are ''dayok'' and ''danglusi''. In modern [[Cebuano language|Cebuano]], ''guinamos'' refers to an entirely different dish, ''[[bagoong]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scott |first1=William Henry |title=Sixteenth-Century Visayan Food and Farming |journal=Philippine Quarterly of Culture and Society |date=1990 |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=291\u2013311 |jstor=29792029 }}</ref><ref name=\"vlb\">{{cite book|author=R. P. Matheo Sanchez|editor =|title =Vocabulario de la lengua Bisaya|chapter =|publisher =Colegio de la Sagrada Compania de Jesus|series =|year =1711|pages=198|url =https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=XTlNAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA198-IA1#v=onepage&q=adobo&f=false|quote=Gamus. up. f Gamusun vel. gamsun. Salar o adobar carne, o pescado; ba cun gagamsun an isda sagan sin saguing, sin chile, sua. &c}}</ref> In [[Hiligaynon language|Hiligaynon]], ''guinamos'' also refers to regional variants of ''[[bagoong]].'' Dishes prepared with vinegar, garlic, salt (later soy sauce), and other spices eventually came to be known solely as ''adobo'', with the original term for the dish now lost to history.<ref name=\"Indigenous\">{{Cite news| last = Ocampo| first = Ambeth.| author-link = Ambeth Ocampo| title = Looking Back: 'Adobo' in many forms| newspaper = Philippine Daily Inquirer| date = February 24, 2009| url = http://opinion.inquirer.net/inquireropinion/columns/view/20090224-190838/Adobo-in-many-forms| accessdate = August 4, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150523031023/http://opinion.inquirer.net/inquireropinion/columns/view/20090224-190838/Adobo-in-many-forms| archivedate = May 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Rappaport\">{{cite book|author=Rappaport, Rachel |title =The Everything Healthy Slow Cooker Cookbook|publisher =Adams Media|year =2010|page=[https://archive.org/details/everythinghealth0000rapp/page/255 255]|isbn = 9781440508486|url =https://archive.org/details/everythinghealth0000rapp|url-access=registration |quote=Philippine Adobo variation. }}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n{{See also|Adobo}}\n[[File:Chicken adobo (Philippines) 2.jpg|thumb|Chicken ''adobo'' with [[broccoli]]]]\nWhile the ''adobo'' dish and cooking process in Filipino cuisine and the general description of ''[[adobo]]'' in [[Spanish cuisine]] share similar characteristics, they refer to different things with different cultural roots.<ref name=\"tayag\"/>  Unlike the Spanish and Latin American ''adobo'', the main ingredients of Philippine ''adobo'' are ingredients native to [[Southeast Asia]], namely [[soy sauce]] (originally salt), [[black peppercorn]]s, and [[Cinnamomum tamala|bay leaves]]. It does not traditionally use [[chili pepper|chilis]], [[paprika]], [[oregano]], or [[tomato]]es. Its only similarity to Spanish and Latin American ''adobo'' is the primary use of vinegar and garlic. Philippine ''adobo'' has a characteristically salty and sour, and often sweet, taste, in contrast to Spanish and Mexican ''adobos'' which are spicier or infused with oregano.<ref name=\"estrella\"/><ref name=\"Zulu2017\">{{cite news |last1=Zulu |first1=Mijon |title=What Is the Difference Between Mexican and Filipino Adobo? |url=https://www.chowhound.com/food-news/191932/what-is-the-difference-between-mexican-and-filipino-adobo/ |accessdate=9 January 2019 |work=Chowhound |date=19 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=This Chicken Adobo Is a Flavor Bomb of Salty-Sour Goodness |url=https://www.cookinglight.com/recipes/chicken-adobo-0 |website=CookingLight |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Pork adobo with shallots.jpg|thumb|left|Pork ''adobo'' with [[shallot]]s]]\nWhile the Philippine ''adobo'' can be considered ''adobo'' in the Spanish sense\u2014a marinated dish\u2014the Philippine usage is much more specific to a cooking process (rather than a specific recipe) and is not restricted to meat.<ref name=\"tayag\"/> Typically, [[pork]] or [[chicken]], or a combination of both, is slowly cooked in [[vinegar]], crushed [[garlic]], [[bay leaf|bay leaves]], [[black pepper]]corns, and [[soy sauce]]. It is served with white [[rice]].<ref name=\"rodell\"/><ref name=Oxford>Alan Davidson & Tom Jaine. (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=JTr-ouCbL2AC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Oxford Companion to Food'']. New York: Oxford University Press. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=JTr-ouCbL2AC&pg=PA5&lpg=#v=onepage&q&f=false 5]. {{ISBN|0-19-280681-5}}.</ref><ref name=\"sifton\">Sifton, Sam. (January 5, 2011). [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/09/magazine/09Food-t-000.html?src=me&ref=general The Cheat: The Adobo Experiment]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved January 7, 2011</ref> It was traditionally cooked in small clay pots (''[[palayok]]'' or ''kulon''); but in modern times, metal pots or [[wok]]s (''kawali'') are used instead.<ref name=\"kittler\">{{cite book|author1=Kittler, Pamela Goyan   |author2=Sucher, Kathryn  |lastauthoramp=yes |title =The Culinary culture of the Philippines|publisher =Cengage Learning|year =2007|page=371|isbn = 9780495115410|url =https://books.google.com/?id=eKdbaMY5AHEC&lpg=PA371&dq=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&pg=PA371#v=onepage&q=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&f=false}}</ref>\n\nThere are numerous variants of the ''adobo'' recipe in the Philippines.<ref name=\"Indigenous\"/> The most basic ingredient of ''adobo'' is vinegar, which is usually [[vinegar#Varieties|coconut vinegar]], [[rice vinegar]], or [[cane vinegar]] (although sometimes [[white wine]] or [[cider vinegar]] can also be used). Almost every ingredient can be changed according to personal preference. Even people in the same household can cook ''adobo'' in significantly different ways.<ref name=\"tayag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=784792|title=The adobo identity (crisis) |author=Claude Tayag|date=March 8, 2012|publisher=The Philippine Star|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"sifton\"/> \n[[File:7483Foods deli of Bulacan 13.jpg|''Adobong sitaw'' ([[green bean]]s)|thumb|''Adobong sitaw'' ([[green bean]]s and pork)]]\nA rarer version without soy sauce is known as ''adobong puti'' (\"white ''adobo''\"), which uses salt instead, to contrast it with ''adobong itim'' (\"black adobo\"), the more prevalent versions with soy sauce.<ref name=\"sy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/baguio/feature/2011/08/11/admirable-adobo-172295|title=The Admirable Adobo |author=Artie Sy|date=August 11, 2011|publisher=Sun Star|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"fpress\">{{cite web|url=http://foodpress.com/features/adobong-puti-white-chicken-adobo-for-kulinarya-cooking-club/|date=June 19, 2011|title=Adobong Puti (White Chicken Adobo) for Kulinarya Cooking Club|publisher=FoodPress|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> ''Adobong puti'' is often regarded as the closest to the original version of the Pre-Hispanic ''adobo''.<ref name=\"tayag\"/><ref name=\"mmwhite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marketmanila.com/archives/the-best-pork-adobo-a-la-marketman|title=The BEST Pork Adobo a la Marketman|date=May 7, 2008|publisher=Market Manila|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> It is similar to another dish known as ''[[pinatisan]]'', where [[patis (sauce)|patis]] (fish sauce) is used instead of vinegar.<ref name=\"adb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adobongblog.com/2011/10/adobong-puti-white-adobo.html|title=Adobong Puti (White Adobo) |date=October 4, 2011|publisher=AdobongBlog|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAdobong dilaw (\"yellow ''adobo''\"), which uses ''kalawag'' ([[turmeric]]) to provide the yellow colouring as well as adding in a different flavour, can be found in the [[Visayas]] and [[Mindanao]] regions. \n\nIn the region of [[Negros Occidental]], known for [[sugarcane]] production in the Philippines, a sweet variant of adobo called ''[[humba]]'' is often served in feasts and other special occasions, which is made with fatty chunks of pork belly, hard boiled eggs, banana blossoms, and the addition of [[brown sugar]]. \n\nThe proportion (or even the presence) of ingredients like soy sauce, bay leaves, garlic, or black pepper can vary. Other ingredients can sometimes be used; like ''[[siling labuyo]]'', [[bird's eye chili]], [[Jalape\u00f1o|jalape\u00f1o pepper]], [[Bell pepper|red bell pepper]], [[olive oil]], [[onion]]s, [[brown sugar]], [[potato]]es, or [[pineapple]]. It may also be further browned in the oven, pan-fried, deep-fried, or even grilled to get crisped edges.<ref name=\"sifton\"/><ref name=\"Cordero-Fernando\">{{cite book|author=Cordero-Fernando, Gilda |title =The Culinary culture of the Philippines|publisher =Bancom Audiovision Corp|year =1976|pages=11\u201313}}</ref>\n\n''Adobo'' has been called the quintessential Philippine stew, served with rice both at daily meals and at feasts.<ref name=\"Oxford\" /> It is commonly packed for Filipino [[Mountaineering|mountaineers]] and travelers because it keeps well without refrigeration. Its relatively long shelf-life is due to one of its primary ingredients, [[vinegar]], which inhibits the growth of [[bacteria]].<ref name=\"rodell\">{{cite book|author=Rodell, Paul A. |title =Culture and Customs of the Philippines|publisher =Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Westport, CT|series =Culture and Customs of Asia|year =2002|page=102|isbn = 9780313304156|url =https://books.google.com/?id=y1CVR74_KHQC&lpg=PA102&dq=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&pg=PA102#v=onepage&q=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Variations==\n[[File:Fely J's Adobo.jpg|thumb|Beef ''adobo'']]\nBased on the main ingredients, the most common ''adobo'' dishes are ''adobong manok'', in which chicken is used, and ''adobong baboy'', in which pork is used. ''Adobong baka'' ([[beef]]), along with ''adobong manok'' ([[chicken]]), is more popular among Muslim Filipinos.<ref name=\"beef\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bohol.ph/recipe.php?id=71|title=Adobong Baka (Beef)|author=Jeroen Hellingman|date=March 28, 2003|publisher=Bohol.ph|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> Other meat sources may also be used, such as ''adobong pug\u00f2'' ([[quail]]), ''adobong itik'' (duck), ''adobong kambing'' (goat).<ref name=\"tayag\" /> There are also seafood variants which can include fish (''adobong isda''), [[catfish]] (''adobong hito''), [[shrimp]] (''adobong hipon''), and [[squid]] or [[cuttlefish]] (''adobong pusit''). It can even be used to cook [[vegetable]]s and [[fruit]]s,<ref name=\"kittler\"/> like [[Ipomoea aquatica|water spinach]] (''adobong kangkong''), [[bamboo shoot]]s (''adobong labong''), [[eggplant]] (''adobong talong''), [[banana flower]]s (''adobong pus\u00f4 ng saging''), and [[okra]] (''adobong okra'').<ref name=\"Alejandro\">{{cite book|author=Alejandro, Reynaldo G. \t|title =The Philippine Cookbook|publisher =Penguin|year =1985|pages=52\u201360|isbn =  9780399511448|url =https://books.google.com/?id=HUaDoUF0tRwC&dq=Adobong+pusit}}</ref><ref>AdoboChef (January 5, 2011). [http://www.adobochef.com Traditional Adobo Recipes] Retrieved June 22, 2012</ref> \n\nEven more exotic versions include ''adobong saw\u00e2'' ([[snake]]),<ref name=\"sawa\">{{cite web|url=http://cebutourist.com/exotic-food-finds-in-cebu/|title=Only for the Daring: Exotic Food Finds in Cebu|date=June 17, 2011|publisher=Cebutourist|accessdate=November 7, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119031627/http://cebutourist.com/exotic-food-finds-in-cebu/|archivedate=January 19, 2013}}</ref> ''adobong palak\u00e2'' ([[Frog|frogs]]),<ref name=\"spc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sanpablocity.com.ph/san-pablo-city-recipe/309-adobong-palaka.html|title=Adobong Palaka |date= October 14, 2010|publisher=San Pablo City|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> [[Kapampangan cuisine|Kapampangan]] ''adobung kamaru'' ([[mole cricket]]s),<ref name=\"tayag\" /> and the ''adobong atay at balunbalunan'' ([[chicken liver]] and [[gizzard]]).<ref name=\"atay\">{{cite web|url=http://reelandgrill.blogspot.com/2010/12/adobong-atay-at-balunbalunan-chicken.html|title=Adobong Atay at Balunbalunan (Chicken Liver and Gizzard)|publisher=Reel and Grill |date=December 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThere are also regional variations. In southern [[Luzon]] (Bicol region),  and [[Muslim]] [[Zamboanga City|Zamboanga]], for example, it is common to see ''adobo'' cooked with [[coconut milk]] (known as ''adobo [[Ginataan|sa gat\u00e2]]''). In [[Cavite province|Cavite]], mashed [[Liver (food)|pork liver]] is added. In [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], [[turmeric]] was added, giving the dish a distinct yellowish color (known as ''adobong dilaw'', \"yellow adobo\").<ref name=\"rodell\" /><ref name=\"sifton\" />\n\n''Adobo'' has also become a favorite of Filipino-based fusion cuisine, with avant-garde cooks coming up with variants such as \"Japanese-style\" pork adobo.<ref name=\"Manipon20160201\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.tribune.net.ph/life-style/japanese-style-adobo-and-other-delicious-things-you-can-cook-in-a-microwave-oven |title=Japanese-style adobo and other delicious things you can cook  in a microwave oven |last=Manipon  |first=Roel Hoang  |date=2016-02-01 |work=The Daily Tribune |access-date=2018-03-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201231858/http://www.tribune.net.ph/life-style/japanese-style-adobo-and-other-delicious-things-you-can-cook-in-a-microwave-oven |archive-date=2016-02-01 |url-status=live |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"100px\" caption=\"Philippine ''adobo'' variants\">\nFile:Filipino Chicken Adobo.JPG|Chicken ''adobo'' over rice\nFile:Chicken Adobo In Coconut Milk (adobong Manok Sa Gata).jpg|''Adobo sa gata''<br>with [[coconut milk]]\nFile:Pork adobo.jpg|Pork ''adobo'' with [[pineapple]]s\nFile:Adobong talong or Eggplant adobo (Philippines).jpg|''Adobong talong''<br>(eggplant)\nFile:Fely J's Fried Crickets (Adobong Kamaru).jpg|''Adobung kamaru''<br>([[mole cricket]]s)\nFile:Adobong kangkong (Philippines).jpg|''Adobong kangkong''<br>([[water spinach]])\nFile:Adobong hipon (Shrimp adobo, Philippines).jpg|''Adobong hipon'' (shrimp)\nFile:Adobong pusit (squid adobo) - Philippines.jpg|''Adobong pusit'' (squid)\nFile:Vegetarian Filipino Adobo.jpg|[[Vegetarian]] ''adobo''\nFile:Chickenini - Adobong Chicken Intestines (Isaw).jpg|''Adobong [[isaw]] ng manok'' (chicken intestines)\n</gallery>\n\n==Other uses==\nOutside of the dish itself, the flavor of ''adobo'' has been developed commercially and adapted to other foods.  A number of local Philippine snack products such as [[Cornick (food)|cornick]]s, [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]], chips, noodle soups, and corn crackers, market their items as \"adobo flavored\".\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Philippines|Food}}\n*[[Humba]]\n*[[Pata tim]]\n*[[Paksiw]]\n* [[Dinuguan]]\n*[[Cuisine of the Philippines]]\n* [[List of Philippine dishes]]\n* [[Kare-kare]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Adobo (Filipino cuisine)}}\n{{Cookbook|Adobo}}\n{{Philippine cuisine}}\n{{Marinades}}\n{{Symbols of the Philippines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adobo (Filipino Cuisine)}}\n[[Category:Philippine cuisine]]\n[[Category:National dishes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Filipino cooking process}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Philippine adobo\n| image            = Chicken adobo.jpg\n| caption          = Chicken ''adobo''\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Philippines]]\n| region           = \n| national_cuisine = [[Filipino cuisine]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Main course]]\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[Meat]] ([[beef]], [[chicken]], [[pork]]), [[seafood]], or vegetables; [[soy sauce]], [[vinegar]], [[cooking oil]], [[garlic]], [[black pepper]]corn, [[bay leaf]]\n| variations       = Some sugar for sweet-salty taste\n| calories         = \n*Chicken: 107 [[Calorie|kcal]]\n*Pork: 342 [[Calorie|kcal]]\n*Beef: 349 \n| calories_ref     =<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfitnesspal.com/food/calories/generic-filipino-pork-adobo-325988545|title=Calories in Filipino Pork Adobo - Calories and Nutrition Facts - MyFitnessPal.com|website=www.myfitnesspal.com}})</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fatsecret.com/Diary.aspx?pa=fjrd&rid=255665|title=Calories in Beef Adobo and Nutrition Facts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fatsecret.com/calories-nutrition/generic/chicken-adobo|title=Calories in Chicken Adobo and Nutrition Facts|website=www.fatsecret.com}}</ref>\n| other            = \n| similar_dish     = [[paksiw]], [[kinilaw]]\n}}\n\n'''Philippine ''adobo''''' (from [[Spanish language|Spanish]] ''adobar'': \"[[marination|marinade]],\" \"sauce\" or \"seasoning\") is a popular Filipino dish and cooking process in [[Philippine cuisine]] that involves [[meat]], [[seafood]], or [[Vegetable|vegetables]] marinated in [[vinegar]], [[soy sauce]], [[garlic]], and [[Black pepper|black peppercorns]], which is browned in [[Cooking oil|oil]], and simmered in the marinade. It has occasionally been considered the unofficial national dish in the [[Philippines]].<ref name=\"dewitt\">{{cite book|author=DeWitt, Dave |title =1,001 Best Hot and Spicy Recipes|publisher =[[Agate Publishing]]|year =2010|page=428|isbn = 9781572841130|url =https://books.google.com/?id=sNLKs8LO35kC&lpg=PA428&dq=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&pg=PA428#v=onepage&q=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Pangilinan, Jr. | first = Leon | title = In Focus: 9 Facts You May Not Know About Philippine National Symbols | url=http://ncca.gov.ph/about-culture-and-arts/in-focus/9-facts-you-may-not-know-about-philippine-national-symbols/ | date = 3 October 2014 | accessdate = 8 January 2019 | publisher = [[National Commission for Culture and the Arts]]}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe cooking method for the Philippine ''adobo'' is indigenous to the [[Philippines]]. [[History of the Philippines (900\u20131521)|Pre-colonial]] Filipinos often cooked or prepared their food with [[vinegar]] and salt to keep them fresh longer in the [[tropical]] climate of the Philippines. Vinegar, in particular, is one of the most important ingredients in Filipino cuisine, with four main traditional types: [[coconut vinegar]], [[cane vinegar]], [[nipa palm vinegar]], and [[kaong palm vinegar]], all of which are linked to traditional [[Alcoholic drink|alcohol]] [[fermentation]].<ref name=\"hosking\"/><ref name=\"Ponseca\"/>\n[[File:Chicken Adobo over rice.jpg|thumb|left|Chicken ''adobo'' on white [[rice]]]]\nThere are four main traditional cooking methods using vinegar that are still widely prevalent in the Philippines today: ''[[kinilaw]]'' (raw seafood in vinegar and spices), ''[[paksiw]]'' (a broth of meat with vinegar and spices), ''[[sangkutsa]]'' (pre-cooking meat by [[braising]] them in vinegar and spices), and finally ''adobo'' (a stew of vinegar, garlic, salt/soy sauce, and other spices).<ref name=\"asianjournal.wordpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://asianjournal.wordpress.com/2008/07/14/adobo-a-history-of-the-countrys-national-dish/|title=ADOBO: A History of the Country's National Dish|date=14 July 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"rodell\"/><ref name=\"estrella\"/><ref name=\"hosking\"/> It is believed that ''paksiw'', ''sangkutsa'', and ''adobo'' were all derivations of ''kinilaw''. They are also related to cooking techniques like ''[[sinigang]]'' and ''[[pinangat na isda]]'' that also have a sour broth, albeit using native fruits like [[calamansi]], [[tamarind]], unripe [[mango]]es, [[bilimbi]], [[Sandoricum koetjape|santol]], and [[carambola|star fruit]] instead of vinegar.<ref name=\"Ponseca\">{{cite book |last1=Ponseca |first1=Nicole |last2=Trinidad |first2=Miguel |title=I Am a Filipino: And This Is How We Cook |date=2018 |publisher=Artisan Books |isbn=9781579658823 |url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=63BMDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Spanish Empire]] colonized the [[Philippines]] in the late 16th century and early 17th century, they encountered the ''adobo'' cooking process. It was first recorded in the dictionary ''[[Vocabulario de la Lengua Tagala]]'' (1613) compiled by the Spanish [[Franciscan]] missionary [[Pedro de San Buenaventura]]. He referred to it as ''adobo de los naturales'' (\"''[[adobo]]'' of the native peoples\").<ref name=\"rodell\"/><ref name=\"estrella\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pepper.ph/the-history-of-adobo/|title=Adobo: The History of A National Favorite|author= Estrella, Serna|date=June 22, 2013|publisher=Pepper.ph|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"hosking\">{{cite book|author=Lim-Castillo, Pia|editor =Hosking, Richard|title =Authenticity in the Kitchen|chapter =Traditional Philippine Vinegars and their Role in Shaping the Culinary Culture|publisher =Prospect Books|series =Proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery 2005|year =2006|page=296&ndash;298|isbn =9781903018477|chapter-url =https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=HflTVd898PAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> \n\nThe Spanish also applied the term ''adobo'' to any native dish that was marinated before consumption. In the 1794 edition of ''Vocabulario de la lengua Tagala'', it was applied to ''quilau\u00ecn'' (''[[kinilaw]]'') a related but different dish which also primarily uses vinegar.<ref name=\"vlt\">{{cite book|author=Domingo de los Santos\n|editor =|title =Vocabulario de la lengua Tagala, primera y segunda parte: en la primera, se pone primero el Castellano, y despues el Tagalo : y en la segunda al contrario, que son las rayzes simples con sus accentos|chapter =|publisher =N.S. de Loreto |series =|year =1794|page=42|isbn =|quote=Adobo. Quilau\u00ecn. (pc) toman s\u00e0l vinagre, y ch\u00edle, y lo echan en la carne, pescado, \u00f2 tripas de venado; y asi medio crudo lo comen . . . Este mismo genero de adobo sirve para las yervas como ensalada.\n|url =https://books.google.com/?id=XitOAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA42&dq=vocabulario+de+la+lengua+tagala+adobo#v=onepage&q=vocabulario%20de%20la%20lengua%20tagala%20adobo&f=false}}</ref> In ''Vocabulario de la lengua Bisaya'' (1711), the term ''guinamus'' (verb form: ''gamus'') was used to refer to any kind of marinades (''adobo''), from fish to pork. Other terms for precolonial ''adobo''-like dishes among the Visayan peoples are ''dayok'' and ''danglusi''. In modern [[Cebuano language|Cebuano]], ''guinamos'' refers to an entirely different dish, ''[[bagoong]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scott |first1=William Henry |title=Sixteenth-Century Visayan Food and Farming |journal=Philippine Quarterly of Culture and Society |date=1990 |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=291\u2013311 |jstor=29792029 }}</ref><ref name=\"vlb\">{{cite book|author=R. P. Matheo Sanchez|editor =|title =Vocabulario de la lengua Bisaya|chapter =|publisher =Colegio de la Sagrada Compania de Jesus|series =|year =1711|pages=198|url =https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=XTlNAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA198-IA1#v=onepage&q=adobo&f=false|quote=Gamus. up. f Gamusun vel. gamsun. Salar o adobar carne, o pescado; ba cun gagamsun an isda sagan sin saguing, sin chile, sua. &c}}</ref> In [[Hiligaynon language|Hiligaynon]], ''guinamos'' also refers to regional variants of ''[[bagoong]].'' Dishes prepared with vinegar, garlic, salt (later soy sauce), and other spices eventually came to be known solely as ''adobo'', with the original term for the dish now lost to history.<ref name=\"Indigenous\">{{Cite news| last = Ocampo| first = Ambeth.| author-link = Ambeth Ocampo| title = Looking Back: 'Adobo' in many forms| newspaper = Philippine Daily Inquirer| date = February 24, 2009| url = http://opinion.inquirer.net/inquireropinion/columns/view/20090224-190838/Adobo-in-many-forms| accessdate = August 4, 2010| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150523031023/http://opinion.inquirer.net/inquireropinion/columns/view/20090224-190838/Adobo-in-many-forms| archivedate = May 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Rappaport\">{{cite book|author=Rappaport, Rachel |title =The Everything Healthy Slow Cooker Cookbook|publisher =Adams Media|year =2010|page=[https://archive.org/details/everythinghealth0000rapp/page/255 255]|isbn = 9781440508486|url =https://archive.org/details/everythinghealth0000rapp|url-access=registration |quote=Philippine Adobo variation. }}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n{{See also|Adobo}}\n[[File:Chicken adobo (Philippines) 2.jpg|thumb|Chicken ''adobo'' with [[broccoli]]]]\nWhile the ''adobo'' dish and cooking process in Filipino cuisine and the general description of ''[[adobo]]'' in [[Spanish cuisine]] share similar characteristics, they refer to different things with different cultural roots.<ref name=\"tayag\"/>  Unlike the Spanish and Latin American ''adobo'', the main ingredients of Philippine ''adobo'' are ingredients native to [[Southeast Asia]], namely [[soy sauce]] (originally salt), [[black peppercorn]]s, and [[Cinnamomum tamala|bay leaves]]. It does not traditionally use [[chili pepper|chilis]], [[paprika]], [[oregano]], or [[tomato]]es. Its only similarity to Spanish and Latin American ''adobo'' is the primary use of vinegar and garlic. Philippine ''adobo'' has a characteristically salty and sour, and often sweet, taste, in contrast to Spanish and Mexican ''adobos'' which are spicier or infused with oregano.<ref name=\"estrella\"/><ref name=\"Zulu2017\">{{cite news |last1=Zulu |first1=Mijon |title=What Is the Difference Between Mexican and Filipino Adobo? |url=https://www.chowhound.com/food-news/191932/what-is-the-difference-between-mexican-and-filipino-adobo/ |accessdate=9 January 2019 |work=Chowhound |date=19 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=This Chicken Adobo Is a Flavor Bomb of Salty-Sour Goodness |url=https://www.cookinglight.com/recipes/chicken-adobo-0 |website=CookingLight |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Pork adobo with shallots.jpg|thumb|left|Pork ''adobo'' with [[shallot]]s]]\nWhile the Philippine ''adobo'' can be considered ''adobo'' in the Spanish sense\u2014a marinated dish\u2014the Philippine usage is much more specific to a cooking process (rather than a specific recipe) and is not restricted to meat.<ref name=\"tayag\"/> Typically, [[pork]] or [[chicken]], or a combination of both, is slowly cooked in [[vinegar]], crushed [[garlic]], [[bay leaf|bay leaves]], [[black pepper]]corns, and [[soy sauce]]. It is served with white [[rice]].<ref name=\"rodell\"/><ref name=Oxford>Alan Davidson & Tom Jaine. (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=JTr-ouCbL2AC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Oxford Companion to Food'']. New York: Oxford University Press. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=JTr-ouCbL2AC&pg=PA5&lpg=#v=onepage&q&f=false 5]. {{ISBN|0-19-280681-5}}.</ref><ref name=\"sifton\">Sifton, Sam. (January 5, 2011). [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/09/magazine/09Food-t-000.html?src=me&ref=general The Cheat: The Adobo Experiment]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved January 7, 2011</ref> It was traditionally cooked in small clay pots (''[[palayok]]'' or ''kulon''); but in modern times, metal pots or [[wok]]s (''kawali'') are used instead.<ref name=\"kittler\">{{cite book|author1=Kittler, Pamela Goyan   |author2=Sucher, Kathryn  |lastauthoramp=yes |title =The Culinary culture of the Philippines|publisher =Cengage Learning|year =2007|page=371|isbn = 9780495115410|url =https://books.google.com/?id=eKdbaMY5AHEC&lpg=PA371&dq=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&pg=PA371#v=onepage&q=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&f=false}}</ref>\n\nThere are numerous variants of the ''adobo'' recipe in the Philippines.<ref name=\"Indigenous\"/> The most basic ingredient of ''adobo'' is vinegar, which is usually [[vinegar#Varieties|coconut vinegar]], [[rice vinegar]], or [[cane vinegar]] (although sometimes [[white wine]] or [[cider vinegar]] can also be used). Almost every ingredient can be changed according to personal preference. Even people in the same household can cook ''adobo'' in significantly different ways.<ref name=\"tayag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=784792|title=The adobo identity (crisis) |author=Claude Tayag|date=March 8, 2012|publisher=The Philippine Star|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"sifton\"/> \n[[File:7483Foods deli of Bulacan 13.jpg|''Adobong sitaw'' ([[green bean]]s)|thumb|''Adobong sitaw'' ([[green bean]]s and pork)]]\nA rarer version without soy sauce is known as ''adobong puti'' (\"white ''adobo''\"), which uses salt instead, to contrast it with ''adobong itim'' (\"black adobo\"), the more prevalent versions with soy sauce.<ref name=\"sy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/baguio/feature/2011/08/11/admirable-adobo-172295|title=The Admirable Adobo |author=Artie Sy|date=August 11, 2011|publisher=Sun Star|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"fpress\">{{cite web|url=http://foodpress.com/features/adobong-puti-white-chicken-adobo-for-kulinarya-cooking-club/|date=June 19, 2011|title=Adobong Puti (White Chicken Adobo) for Kulinarya Cooking Club|publisher=FoodPress|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> ''Adobong puti'' is often regarded as the closest to the original version of the Pre-Hispanic ''adobo''.<ref name=\"tayag\"/><ref name=\"mmwhite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marketmanila.com/archives/the-best-pork-adobo-a-la-marketman|title=The BEST Pork Adobo a la Marketman|date=May 7, 2008|publisher=Market Manila|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> It is similar to another dish known as ''[[pinatisan]]'', where [[patis (sauce)|patis]] (fish sauce) is used instead of vinegar.<ref name=\"adb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adobongblog.com/2011/10/adobong-puti-white-adobo.html|title=Adobong Puti (White Adobo) |date=October 4, 2011|publisher=AdobongBlog|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAdobong dilaw (\"yellow ''adobo''\"), which uses ''kalawag'' ([[turmeric]]) to provide the yellow colouring as well as adding in a different flavour, can be found in the [[Visayas]] and [[Mindanao]] regions. \n\nIn the region of [[Negros Occidental]], known for [[sugarcane]] production in the Philippines, a sweet variant of adobo called ''[[humba]]'' is often served in feasts and other special occasions, which is made with fatty chunks of pork belly, hard boiled eggs, banana blossoms, and the addition of [[brown sugar]]. \n\nThe proportion (or even the presence) of ingredients like soy sauce, bay leaves, garlic, or black pepper can vary. Other ingredients can sometimes be used; like ''[[siling labuyo]]'', [[bird's eye chili]], [[Jalape\u00f1o|jalape\u00f1o pepper]], [[Bell pepper|red bell pepper]], [[olive oil]], [[onion]]s, [[brown sugar]], [[potato]]es, or [[pineapple]]. It may also be further browned in the oven, pan-fried, deep-fried, or even grilled to get crisped edges.<ref name=\"sifton\"/><ref name=\"Cordero-Fernando\">{{cite book|author=Cordero-Fernando, Gilda |title =The Culinary culture of the Philippines|publisher =Bancom Audiovision Corp|year =1976|pages=11\u201313}}</ref>\n\n''Adobo'' has been called the quintessential Philippine stew, served with rice both at daily meals and at feasts.<ref name=\"Oxford\" /> It is commonly packed for Filipino [[Mountaineering|mountaineers]] and travelers because it keeps well without refrigeration. Its relatively long shelf-life is due to one of its primary ingredients, [[vinegar]], which inhibits the growth of [[bacteria]].<ref name=\"rodell\">{{cite book|author=Rodell, Paul A. |title =Culture and Customs of the Philippines|publisher =Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Westport, CT|series =Culture and Customs of Asia|year =2002|page=102|isbn = 9780313304156|url =https://books.google.com/?id=y1CVR74_KHQC&lpg=PA102&dq=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&pg=PA102#v=onepage&q=Philippine%20Adobo%20variation&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Variations==\n[[File:Fely J's Adobo.jpg|thumb|Beef ''adobo'']]\nBased on the main ingredients, the most common ''adobo'' dishes are ''adobong manok'', in which chicken is used, and ''adobong baboy'', in which pork is used. ''Adobong baka'' ([[beef]]), along with ''adobong manok'' ([[chicken]]), is more popular among Muslim Filipinos.<ref name=\"beef\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bohol.ph/recipe.php?id=71|title=Adobong Baka (Beef)|author=Jeroen Hellingman|date=March 28, 2003|publisher=Bohol.ph|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> Other meat sources may also be used, such as ''adobong pug\u00f2'' ([[quail]]), ''adobong itik'' (duck), ''adobong kambing'' (goat).<ref name=\"tayag\" /> There are also seafood variants which can include fish (''adobong isda''), [[catfish]] (''adobong hito''), [[shrimp]] (''adobong hipon''), and [[squid]] or [[cuttlefish]] (''adobong pusit''). It can even be used to cook [[vegetable]]s and [[fruit]]s,<ref name=\"kittler\"/> like [[Ipomoea aquatica|water spinach]] (''adobong kangkong''), [[bamboo shoot]]s (''adobong labong''), [[eggplant]] (''adobong talong''), [[banana flower]]s (''adobong pus\u00f4 ng saging''), and [[okra]] (''adobong okra'').<ref name=\"Alejandro\">{{cite book|author=Alejandro, Reynaldo G. \t|title =The Philippine Cookbook|publisher =Penguin|year =1985|pages=52\u201360|isbn =  9780399511448|url =https://books.google.com/?id=HUaDoUF0tRwC&dq=Adobong+pusit}}</ref><ref>AdoboChef (January 5, 2011). [http://www.adobochef.com Traditional Adobo Recipes] Retrieved June 22, 2012</ref> \n\nEven more exotic versions include ''adobong saw\u00e2'' ([[snake]]),<ref name=\"sawa\">{{cite web|url=http://cebutourist.com/exotic-food-finds-in-cebu/|title=Only for the Daring: Exotic Food Finds in Cebu|date=June 17, 2011|publisher=Cebutourist|accessdate=November 7, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119031627/http://cebutourist.com/exotic-food-finds-in-cebu/|archivedate=January 19, 2013}}</ref> ''adobong palak\u00e2'' ([[Frog|frogs]]),<ref name=\"spc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sanpablocity.com.ph/san-pablo-city-recipe/309-adobong-palaka.html|title=Adobong Palaka |date= October 14, 2010|publisher=San Pablo City|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> [[Kapampangan cuisine|Kapampangan]] ''adobung kamaru'' ([[mole cricket]]s),<ref name=\"tayag\" /> and the ''adobong atay at balunbalunan'' ([[chicken liver]] and [[gizzard]]).<ref name=\"atay\">{{cite web|url=http://reelandgrill.blogspot.com/2010/12/adobong-atay-at-balunbalunan-chicken.html|title=Adobong Atay at Balunbalunan (Chicken Liver and Gizzard)|publisher=Reel and Grill |date=December 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThere are also regional variations. In southern [[Luzon]] (Bicol region),  and [[Muslim]] [[Zamboanga City|Zamboanga]], for example, it is common to see ''adobo'' cooked with [[coconut milk]] (known as ''adobo [[Ginataan|sa gat\u00e2]]''). In [[Cavite province|Cavite]], mashed [[Liver (food)|pork liver]] is added. In [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], [[turmeric]] was added, giving the dish a distinct yellowish color (known as ''adobong dilaw'', \"yellow adobo\").<ref name=\"rodell\" /><ref name=\"sifton\" />\n\n''Adobo'' has also become a favorite of Filipino-based fusion cuisine, with avant-garde cooks coming up with variants such as \"Japanese-style\" pork adobo.<ref name=\"Manipon20160201\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.tribune.net.ph/life-style/japanese-style-adobo-and-other-delicious-things-you-can-cook-in-a-microwave-oven |title=Japanese-style adobo and other delicious things you can cook  in a microwave oven |last=Manipon  |first=Roel Hoang  |date=2016-02-01 |work=The Daily Tribune |access-date=2018-03-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201231858/http://www.tribune.net.ph/life-style/japanese-style-adobo-and-other-delicious-things-you-can-cook-in-a-microwave-oven |archive-date=2016-02-01 |url-status=live |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"100px\" caption=\"Philippine ''adobo'' variants\">\nFile:Filipino Chicken Adobo.JPG|Chicken ''adobo'' over rice\nFile:Chicken Adobo In Coconut Milk (adobong Manok Sa Gata).jpg|''Adobo sa gata''<br>with [[coconut milk]]\nFile:Pork adobo.jpg|Pork ''adobo'' with [[pineapple]]s\nFile:Adobong talong or Eggplant adobo (Philippines).jpg|''Adobong talong''<br>(eggplant)\nFile:Fely J's Fried Crickets (Adobong Kamaru).jpg|''Adobung kamaru''<br>([[mole cricket]]s)\nFile:Adobong kangkong (Philippines).jpg|''Adobong kangkong''<br>([[water spinach]])\nFile:Adobong hipon (Shrimp adobo, Philippines).jpg|''Adobong hipon'' (shrimp)\nFile:Adobong pusit (squid adobo) - Philippines.jpg|''Adobong pusit'' (squid)\nFile:Vegetarian Filipino Adobo.jpg|[[Vegetarian]] ''adobo''\nFile:Chickenini - Adobong Chicken Intestines (Isaw).jpg|''Adobong [[isaw]] ng manok'' (chicken intestines)\n</gallery>\n\n==Other uses==\nOutside of the dish itself, the flavor of ''adobo'' has been developed commercially and adapted to other foods.  A number of local Philippine snack products such as [[Cornick (food)|cornick]]s, [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]], chips, noodle soups, and corn crackers, market their items as \"adobo flavored\".\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Philippines|Food}}\n*[[Humba]]\n*[[Pata tim]]\n*[[Paksiw]]\n* [[Dinuguan]]\n*[[Cuisine of the Philippines]]\n* [[List of Philippine dishes]]\n* [[Kare-kare]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Adobo (Filipino cuisine)}}\n{{Cookbook|Adobo}}\n{{Philippine cuisine}}\n{{Marinades}}\n{{Symbols of the Philippines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adobo (Filipino Cuisine)}}\n[[Category:Philippine cuisine]]\n[[Category:National dishes]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromVocabulario de la Lengua TagalatoVocabulario de la lengua tagalausingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippine_adobo"}
