{"title_page": "Demba Ba", "text_new": "{{short description|association football player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Demba Ba\n| image          = Demba_Ba_BJK'14.JPG\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Ba playing for [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] in 2014\n| fullname       = Demba Ba<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tff.org/Default.aspx?pageId=526&kisiId=1721847 |title=Demba Ba |publisher=Turkish Football Federation |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1985|5|25|df=y}}<ref>{{Hugman|22147|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place    = [[S\u00e8vres]], France\n| height         = 1.89 m<ref name=PremProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/4213/Demba-Ba/overview |title=Demba Ba: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub    = [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]]\n| clubnumber     = 19\n| youthyears1    = 1999\u20132000 |youthclubs1 = Port Autonome\n| youthyears2    = 2000\u20132001 |youthclubs2 = Frileuse\n| youthyears3    = 2001\u20132004 |youthclubs3 = Montrouge\n| years1         = 2005\u20132006 |clubs1 = [[FC Rouen|Rouen]]                          |caps1 = 26 |goals1 = 22\n| years2         = 2006\u20132007 |clubs2 = [[R.E. Mouscron|Mouscron]]                  |caps2 = 12 |goals2 = 8\n| years3         = 2007\u20132011 |clubs3 = [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]]     |caps3 = 97 |goals3 = 37\n| years4         = 2011       |clubs4 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]   |caps4 = 12 |goals4 = 7\n| years5         = 2011\u20132013 |clubs5 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]  |caps5 = 54 |goals5 = 29\n| years6         = 2013\u20132014 |clubs6 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]                    |caps6 = 33 |goals6 = 7\n| years7         = 2014\u20132015 |clubs7 = [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]]                  |caps7 = 29 |goals7 = 18\n| years8         = 2015\u20132018 |clubs8 = [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]]  |caps8 = 29 |goals8 = 20\n| years9         = 2017       |clubs9 = \u2192 [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] (loan)         |caps9 = 2  |goals9 = 1\n| years10        = 2018       |clubs10 = [[G\u00f6ztepe S.K.|G\u00f6ztepe]]                   |caps10 = 13  |goals10 = 7\n| years11        = 2018\u20132019     |clubs11= [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]]  |caps11 = 17 |goals11 = 5\n| years12        = 2019\u2013       |clubs12 = [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]]      |caps12 = 25  |goals12 = 12\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 19\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| pcupdate       = 18:59, 15 March 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate       = 29 March 2015\n}}\n'''Demba Ba''' (born 25 May 1985) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for Turkish club [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]] and the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]].\n\nHe made his first-team debut with French team [[FC Rouen|Rouen]] in 2005 before moving to [[R.E. Mouscron|Mouscron]] and onto [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]] in Germany in 2007. In 2011, he moved to [[Premier League]] side [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. He played only 12 games for West Ham and despite being their league top goal scorer in the 2010\u201311 season, they were relegated to the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] and Ba moved to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]. In January 2013, he completed a move to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] for an undisclosed fee, before joining [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] for \u20ac6 million 18 months later. After one season in Turkey, he moved to [[Shanghai Shenhua]] of the [[Chinese Super League]].\n\nBorn and raised in France, Ba has been a full international for Senegal since 2007 and represented the country at the [[2012 Africa Cup of Nations]].\n\n==Early career==\nBa was born in [[S\u00e8vres]], Hauts-de-Seine<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/demba-ba_prs173421/person.shtml |title=Demba Ba |publisher=Eurosport |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> and is the sixth child of seven. He grew up in [[Saint-Valery-en-Caux]], Seine-Maritime. He joined the youth section of ES Mont-Gaillard, located in [[Le Havre]], in 1992, before playing for Port Autonome between 1999 and 2000, and then for Frileuse between 2000 and 2001.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.demba-ba.eu/biography.html|title=Biography of Demba Ba|publisher= Demba Ba official website|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Ba returned to [[Ch\u00e2tillon, Hauts-de-Seine|Ch\u00e2tillon]] and played for Montrouge.<ref name=\"Bio\"/> He played there until 2004, at which point he decided to concentrate on his football.<ref name=\"Bio\"/> Later that year, after unsuccessful trials at [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] and [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]],<ref name=\"Bio\"/> Ba moved to the United Kingdom to seek a professional contract. He was recommended to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] manager [[Ray Lewington]] through his friend [[Gauthier Diafutua]], then a Watford player, but released shortly after Lewington's dismissal. Ba then spent a week on trial at [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]],<ref name=\"Bio\"/> and returned to France after two more unsuccessful trials at Football League sides [[Swansea City]] and [[Gillingham FC|Gillingham]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/20891896 | title = Demba Ba: Barnsley rejection to Chelsea transfer talks | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 2 January 2013 | accessdate = 12 December 2013 | first = Gary | last = Rose}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Rouen===\nBa signed with manager Alain Michel because they were both moving to French club [[FC Rouen|Rouen]] on a one-year contract, and Ba enjoyed a highly successful season with the club.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Mouscron===\nBelgian club [[R.E. Mouscron|Mouscron]] beat off competition from numerous other clubs to win Ba's signature in 2006. Scoring in each of his first three games, he then picked up fractures in his tibia and fibula, and was out of action between August 2006 and April 2007. Following his eight-month recovery period he scored seven goals in nine games, and picked up his first international cap.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===1899 Hoffenheim===\n[[File:Demba Ba Sinsheim.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Ba, pictured in 2009]]\n\nOn 29 August 2007, Ba moved to [[2. Bundesliga]] side [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]] for \u20ac3&nbsp;million. Ba was an integral part of Hoffenheim's [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the [[Bundesliga]] and their successful first season in the Bundesliga, where they finished seventh after leading during the [[Christmas]] break. In that season he scored 14 goals, only missing one game all season. These goals included a hat-trick in a 3\u20133 game against [[VfB Stuttgart|Stuttgart]] on 24 February 2009. In all competitions Ba scored 40 goals in 103 appearances for TSG 1899 Hoffenheim.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tsg-hoffenheim.de/4news.php?d%5Bnr%5D=1950&d%5Babteilung%5D=Startseite |title=1899 Hoffenheim signs Carlos Eduardo and Demba Ba |publisher=TSG 1899 Hoffenheim |accessdate=29 August 2007 |language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927050052/http://www.tsg-hoffenheim.de/4news.php?d%5Bnr%5D=1950&d%5Babteilung%5D=Startseite |archivedate=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\nIn July 2009, he was due to move to [[VfB Stuttgart]], but the move fell through after he failed a medical.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite.html/511232/artikel_Ba-muss-bei-1899-bleiben.html|title=Stuttgart ist das Risiko zu gro\u00df|work=kicker|accessdate=15 January 2011|date=9 July 2009|language=German|trans-title=Stuttgart thinks the risk is too great}}</ref> In December of that year Ba extended his contract at Hoffenheim to 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://achtzehn99.de/obasi-ba-und-compper-verl-ngern-vertr-ge-vorzeitig/ | title = Obasi, Ba und Compper verl\u00e4ngern Vertr\u00e4ge vorzeitig | language = German | date = 16 December 2009 | publisher = TSG 1899 Hoffenheim | accessdate =16 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Move to England====\nBa left Hoffenheim for disputed reasons in January 2011. Claiming the club had gone back on an agreed transfer to a [[Premier League]] club, believed to be [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], he refused to travel to Hoffenheim's winter training camp. In response, Hoffenheim's general manager said his contract would be cancelled, he would face legal action, and he would be fined and prevented from moving to another club for six months.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/9344952.stm | title = Hoffenheim refuse to release Senegal's Demba Ba | publisher = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 6 January 2011 | accessdate =5 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.demba-ba.eu/newsreader-en/items/explanation-from-demba.html|title=Explanation from Demba|publisher=Demba Ba official website|accessdate=6 January 2011|date=6 January 2011}}</ref> The club also later claimed he travelled to England without permission in order to force a move, which they reluctantly agreed needs to happen due to Ba's actions.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/7333438/Hoffenheim-No-Ba-regrets | title = Hoffenheim&nbsp;\u2013 No Ba regrets | first = Thomas | last = Zocher | publisher = Sky Sports | date = 25 November 2011 | accessdate =10 December 2011}}</ref> The club later agreed to a transfer to [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] for a reported fee of \u00a37.1 million, but it fell through after Ba had agreed personal terms but failed his medical for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11661/6661259/ | title = Stoke step up Ba pursuit | publisher = Sky Sports | date = 14 January 2011 | accessdate =10 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11701/6664487/ | title = Ba's Stoke move breaks downl | publisher = Sky Sports | date = 15 January 2011 | accessdate =10 December 2011}}</ref> Expressing disappointment, Stoke City manager [[Tony Pulis]] said \"Obviously they found something which could cause problems later\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/6665036/ | title = Pulis upset over Ba deal | first = Hayley | last = Paterson | publisher = Sky Sports | date = 15 January 2011 | accessdate =10 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving Hoffenheim, the club's general manager Ernst Tanner stated the club stand by their decision selling Ba.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hoffenheim \u2013 No Ba regrets|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11678/7333438/hoffenheim-no-ba-regrets|publisher=Sky Sports|date=25 November 2011|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===West Ham United===\n[[File:DembaBa.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Ba with West Ham United in 2011]]\n\nAfter the collapsed Stoke deal, Ba was sold to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] for an undisclosed fee based on appearances. He signed a three-year contract on 28 January, on a pay as you play basis due to knee problems found in the Stoke medical.<ref name=\"guardian_2011-06-15\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jun/15/demba-ba-west-ham-everton | title = Demba Ba leaves West Ham and looks to the Premier League | newspaper = The Guardian | location = London | first = Jamie | last = Jackson | accessdate =5 January 2012 | date = 15 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.whufc.com/articles/20110128/hammers-capture-ba_2236884_2275381|title=Hammers capture Ba|publisher=West Ham United F.C|accessdate=28 January 2011|date=28 January 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110131054335/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20110128/hammers-capture-ba_2236884_2275381|archivedate=31 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stoke_city/9361494.stm|title=Hoffenheim striker Demba Ba fails Stoke City medical |publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 January 2011|date=15 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_ham_utd/9371608.stm|title=West Ham sign Senegal striker Demba Ba until 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 January 2011|date=28 January 2011}}</ref> Ba's Premier League debut came on 6 February 2011, as a 75th-minute substitute for [[Robbie Keane]] during a 1\u20130 home defeat by [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9385585.stm|title=West Ham 0&nbsp;\u2013 1 Birmingham |publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 February 2011|date=6 February 2011}}</ref> His first goals followed six days later during his full debut, scoring twice in a 3\u20133 draw against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9391009.stm|title=West Brom 3 \u2013 3 West Ham|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=13 February 2011|date=12 February 2011}}</ref> Despite finishing as their top scorer for the season with seven from twelve games including 2 in the last game, Ba's stay with West Ham proved to be short.<ref name=\"BA2010-11\">{{cite web | url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2802#teamTabs=stats | title=West Ham Stats 2010\u201311 | publisher=Soccerbase | accessdate=13 June 2011}}</ref> Following their relegation to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] after a 3\u20132 loss away to [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] he invoked a release clause in his contract allowing him to leave for free. He turned down a \u00a350,000-a-week salary plus a bonus payment of \u00a3500,000 in order to stay in the Premier League with another club, triggering interest from both [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref name=\"guardian_2011-06-15\" /><ref name=\"Barelegation\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9484432.stm | title=Wigan 3\u20132 West Ham | publisher=BBC Sport | date= 15 May 2011 | accessdate=13 June 2011 | last =McNulty | first = Phil}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\n====2011\u201312 season====\nOn 17 June 2011, Ba signed for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on a three-year deal, making his club debut on 13 August 2011 in the 0\u20130 draw against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nufc.co.uk/articles/20110617/ba-seals-united-move_2281670_2377974|title=Ba Seals United Move|publisher=Newcastle United F.C|accessdate=17 June 2011|date=17 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/14429552.stm|title=Newcastle 0\u20130 Arsenal|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 September 2011|date=13 August 2011}}</ref> His first goals for the club came on 24 September 2011 with a [[List of Premier League hat-tricks|hat-trick]] against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in a 3\u20131 home win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/14958133.stm |title=Newcastle 3 \u2013 1 Blackburn|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 September 2011|date=24 September 2011}}</ref> A second hat-trick came in a 3\u20131 away win at Stoke City, taking his league total to 8 and maintaining the club's 11 game unbeaten league start, taking them to 3rd in the league.<ref>{{cite news|last=Magowan|first=Alistair|title=Stoke 1 \u2013 3 Newcastle |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15425921.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=31 October 2011|date=31 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story/_/id/977793/richard-jolly:-newcastle's-lasting-impression?cc=5901 |title=Richard Jolly: Newcastle's lasting impression | publisher = ESPN Soccernet |date=31 October 2011 |accessdate=3 November 2011 |first = Richard | last = Jolly}}</ref> Ba's goalscoring form continued despite Newcastle entering a downward spell, and saw him picked in ESPN.com's Premier League Best XI for the first half of the season, and named [[Premier League Player of the Month]] for December 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/columnist/hirshey_david/id/7379143/all-prem-team-far-david-hirshey-james-tyler|title=ESPN.com's all-Prem team (so far)|date=23 December 2011|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=318012&cc=5901 | title = Baggies extend Toon's winless run | publisher = ESPN Soccernet | date = 21 December 2011 | accessdate =4 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/16173188.stm | title = Newcastle 2 \u2013 3 West Brom | first = Saj | last = Chowdhury | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 21 December 2011 | accessdate =4 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy the time Ba left to play in the January [[2012 Africa Cup of Nations]] his league tally had reached 15, making him second top scorer in the league behind Arsenal's [[Robin van Persie]]. He left for the tournament on a high note, scoring the first in a 3\u20130 home win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 4 January 2012, the team's first victory against the league champions in over a decade.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16343415.stm | title = Newcastle 3 \u2013 0 Man Utd | publisher = BBC Sport | accessdate =5 January 2012 | date = 4 January 2012 | first = Saj | last = Chowdhury}}</ref> While at the Africa Cup of Nations tournament, Ba's Senegal teammate [[Papiss Ciss\u00e9]] also signed for Newcastle.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nufc.co.uk/articles/20120117/newcastle-sign-papiss-cisse_2281670_2580079 | title = Newcastle Sign Papiss Cisse | accessdate =17 January 2012 | publisher = Newcastle United F.C}}</ref> Ba and Ciss\u00e9 returned earlier than expected after Senegal finished bottom of their group, with Ba having missed three Premier League games and two [[2011\u201312 FA Cup|FA Cup]] games, the second of which saw Newcastle knocked out of the cup.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16750126.stm | title=Newcastle's Demba Ba & Demba Cisse to return early from Africa | work=BBC News}}</ref> He returned to action against Aston Villa on their visit to St James' Park on 5 February 2012, his return proved to be a goal scoring one as he netted the opener in the game which Newcastle won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/feb/05/newcastle-united-aston-villa-premier-league | title = Newcastle's 'Double Demba' prove too hot for Aston Villa to handle | newspaper = The Guardian | location = London | date = 5 February 2012 | accessdate =20 March 2012 | first = Louise | last = Taylor}}</ref> This would prove to be Ba's last goal of the season, as he moved to the left of a three pronged attack with Papiss Ciss\u00e9 leading the line, and grabbing 12 goals in the second half of the season. Despite this late season slump, Ba was voted as the best signing of the 2011\u201312 season by Premier League managers in March 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nufc.co.uk/articles/20120314/demba-voted-best-signing_2281670_2658261 | title = Demba Voted Best Signing | publisher = Newcastle United F.C | accessdate = 20 March 2012 | first = Anthony | last = Marshall | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120315160324/http://www.nufc.co.uk/articles/20120314/demba-voted-best-signing_2281670_2658261 | archivedate = 15 March 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He finished the season as Newcastle's leading goal scorer, with 16 goals.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nBa got his season off to a strong start scoring in a 1\u20130 win against [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]], in Landsberg am Lech, Germany on 16 July 2012. He also scored in a 2\u20131 win against [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] which helped Newcastle win the [[Guadiana Trophy]]. In Newcastle's first league game against Tottenham, Ba opened the scoring with a fantastic volleyed effort in a 2\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/261565/report |title=Losing start for Villas-Boas |publisher=Sky Sports |date=18 August 2012}}</ref> On 17 September 2012, he scored Newcastle's 1000th goal of the [[Premier League]] era, after scoring both goals in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Goodison Park]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19540636 | title = Everton 2\u20132 Newcastle | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 17 September 2012 | accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> On 29 September, he scored for the third game in a row as he scored twice in a 2\u20132 draw away to [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], the first a volley, the second however proved controversial as the ball struck his arm before going in.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19684438 | title = Reading 2\u20132 Newcastle | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 29 September 2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was known that Ba had a release clause in his contract valued at \u00a37 million causing speculation of him making a transfer to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/9772105/Chelseas-move-for-Demba-Ba-stalls-over-Newcastle-players-wage-demands.html | title = Chelsea's move for Demba Ba stalls | newspaper = The Daily Telegraph | location = London | date = 31 December 2012 | accessdate = 3 January 2013 | first2 = Luke | last2 = Edwards | first1 = Chris | last1 =  Bascombe}}</ref> This speculation was confirmed by Newcastle manager [[Alan Pardew]] on 2 January 2013 who said that the transfer was \"done\" and Ba would \"go to Chelsea with our blessing.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/9776978/Demba-Ba-heading-to-Chelsea-from-Newcastle-as-70000-a-week-deal-breaks-transfer-deadlock.html | title = Demba Ba heading to Chelsea from Newcastle as \u00a370,000-a-week deal breaks transfer deadlock | newspaper = The Daily Telegraph | location = London | date = 2 January 2013 | accessdate = 3 January 2013 | first = Luke | last = Edwards}}</ref>\n\n===Chelsea===\n[[File:Chelsea FC v Paris Saint-Germain, 8 April 2014 (56).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Ba playing for Chelsea in 2014]]\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nOn 4 January 2013, Ba joined Chelsea for an undisclosed fee. Ba signed a three-and-a-half-year contract, becoming the first ever Senegalese player to join the club. He received the vacant number 29 shirt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ba transfer completed |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3030470/title/ba-transfer-completed |publisher=Chelsea F.C |date=4 January 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105020148/http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3030470/title/ba-transfer-completed |archivedate=5 January 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\nBa made his debut against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in the third round of the [[2012\u201313 FA Cup|FA Cup]] on 5 January. He marked his first appearance for the club by scoring two goals in a 5\u20131 victory for Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jan/05/southampton-chelsea-fa-cup |title=Chelsea's Demba Ba scores two on his debut in rout at Southampton |publisher=The Guardian |date=5 January 2013 |location=London |first=Sachin |last=Nakrani}}</ref> He scored on his home league debut on 16 January in the 2\u20132 draw against the same club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2263502/Chelsea-2-Southampton-2-match-report--More-woe-Rafa-Benitez.html |title=Chelsea 2 Southampton 2: Who can Pep up Blues? Not Rafa, say angry fans after draw  |publisher=Daily Mail |date=16 January 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 February 2013, Ba first played his former team Newcastle in a Premier League match at St. James' Park. In the 32nd minute of the match Ba had a chance to open the scoring but his initial attempt on goal was saved by Newcastle keeper [[Tim Krul]]. Ba managed to head the rebounded ball and in doing so collided with Coloccini. The collision resulted in a broken nose and Ba was substituted in the 43rd minute. Newcastle went on to win the game 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21209228 | title =  Newcastle 3 \u2013 2 Chelsea | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 2 February 2013 | accessdate = 6 February 2013}}</ref> After a run of seven games without scoring, Ba scored in a 1\u20130 win against West Bromwich Albion at Stamford Bridge on 2 March.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21556758 |title=Chelsea interim manager Rafael Benitez ended a turbulent week with the satisfaction of victory as West Bromwich Albion were beaten at Stamford Bridge |publisher=BBC Sport | date=2 March 2013 | accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref> On 1 April, Ba scored a goal from a long [[Juan Mata]] cross in the FA Cup quarter-final replay against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], giving Chelsea a 1\u20130 victory and a spot at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the semi-finals of the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/chelsea-1-0-manchester-united-match-1796483|title=Chelsea 1\u20130 Man United: Unforgettable Ba strike settles rather forgettable FA Cup replay |work=Daily Mirror |date=1 April 2013| accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> He was cup-tied for Chelsea's victorious [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/demba-ba-winning-cups-means-more-than-top-four-finish-8580088.html |title=Demba Ba: Winning cups means more than top-four finish |publisher=Standard |date=19 April 2013 |accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\n[[File:Demba ba chelsea.JPG|thumb|Ba training with Chelsea before a [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] match]]\n\nFor the [[2013\u201314 Chelsea F.C. season|2013\u201314 season]], Ba's squad number was switched from 29 to 19, his squad number while at [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle]]. In the summer transfer window, Ba was subjected of a transfer bid from his former clubs Newcastle United,<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer news: Sky sources: Newcastle keen to re-sign Demba Ba from Chelsea|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8893259/transfer-news-sky-sources-newcastle-keen-to-re-sign-demba-ba-from-chelsea|publisher=Sky Sports|date=28 August 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> West Ham United<ref>{{cite news|title=West Ham boss Sam Allardyce sets sights on Demba Ba|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/sport/football/332354/West-Ham-boss-Sam-Allardyce-sets-sights-on-Demba-Ba|publisher=Daily Star|date=14 August 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Ba was on the verge of joining Arsenal on a season-long loan, but the move fell through.<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer Deadline Day: Demba Ba not going to Arsenal according to Sky sources|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8903615/transfer-deadline-day-demba-ba-not-going-to-arsenal-according-to-sky-sources|publisher=Sky Sports|date=3 September 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> It was later revealed that the move fell through thanks to Chelsea intervention,<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea block Arsenal Demba Ba move as Blues boss Jose Mourinho sees Arsene Wenger's men as title rivals|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/demba-bas-move-arsenal-blocked-2246401?|work=Daily Mirror|date=2 September 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> though Ba himself considered moving to Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Demba Ba focused on Chelsea future after Arsenal interest|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24131190|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 September 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe scored his first goal of the season after coming on as a substitute in [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] match against [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke]] in a 3\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71808#matchReport |title=MATCH REPORT: CHELSEA 3 SCHALKE 0 |publisher=Chelsea FC |date=6 November 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101160233/http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71808 |archivedate=1 January 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Ba's first [[2013\u201314 Premier League|Premier League]] goal of the season sealed Chelsea's 3\u20131 victory over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71170#matchReport |title=MATCH REPORT: CHELSEA 3 SOUTHAMPTON 1 |publisher=Chelsea FC |date=1 December 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214041552/http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71170 |archivedate=14 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> He made his first Champions League start on 11 December 2013 and he scored the only goal of the game, as Chelsea won 1\u20130 against [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71811#matchReport |title=MATCH REPORT: CHELSEA 1 STEAUA BUCHAREST 0 |publisher=Chelsea FC |date=11 December 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213012121/http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71811#matchReport |archivedate=13 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> On 8 March 2014, he scored twice after coming on as a 76th-minute substitute in a 4\u20130 win over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26396251|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Chelsea 4\u20130 Tottenham Hotspur |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=8 March 2014|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 2014, Ba scored an 87th-minute goal in the Champions League quarter-final second-leg against [[Paris Saint-Germain]] to send Chelsea through to the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26914647 | title =  Chelsea 2\u20130 Paris St-Germain | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 8 April 2014 | accessdate = 9 April 2014 | first = Phil | last = McNulty}}</ref> On 13 April, he scored the winning goal as Chelsea won 1\u20130 at [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26908679|title=Swansea 0\u20131 Chelsea|date=13 April 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> On 27 April, during Chelsea's third final match against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Steven Gerrard]] slipped over while receiving a pass which allowed Ba to score, resulting in Chelsea winning the game 2\u20130, helping them to stay in the race for the Premier League title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebiglead.com/2014/04/27/steven-gerrards-slip-gifted-demba-ba-a-crucial-goal-in-the-epl-title-race/|title=Gerrard slip gives Chelsea goal|date=27 April 2014 | accessdate = 27 April 2014}}</ref> Having only scored 14 goals since his arrival in January 2013, Ba fell behind fellow strikers [[Samuel Eto'o]] and [[Fernando Torres]], having spent most of the season being on the sidelines.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea striker Demba Ba happy with performance in 3\u20131 win over Norwich|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8962816/chelsea-striker-demba-ba-happy-with-performance-in-3-1-win-over-norwich|publisher=Sky Sports|date=7 October 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> After the arrival of [[Diego Costa]] in the summer, Chelsea decided to allow Ba to search for a new club despite his intention to stay for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer news: Demba Ba expects to still be at Chelsea next season|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/9322604/transfer-news-demba-ba-expects-to-still-be-at-chelsea-next-season|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=23 May 2014|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Be\u015fikta\u015f===\n[[File:Demba Ba - John Terry.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Ba with former teammate [[John Terry]] in 2014]]\n\nOn 16 July 2014, [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.]] of the Turkish [[S\u00fcper Lig]] signed Ba from Chelsea for \u20ac6 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kap.gov.tr/bildirim-sorgulari/bildirim-detayi.aspx?id=371845|title=Demba Ba'n\u0131n transferine ili\u015fkin olarak Chelsea kul\u00fcb\u00fc ile anla\u015fmaya var\u0131lm\u0131\u015ft\u0131r|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=18 July 2014| language = tr}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ba moves to Besiktas|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2014/07/ba-moves-to-besiktas.html|work=[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea.com]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=18 July 2014}}</ref> He was given the number 9 shirt.<ref name=nine>{{cite news|last=Kent|first=David|title=Demba Ba will wear No 9 shirt at Besiktas after completing his move from Chelsea|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2694288/Demba-Ba-tweets-Im-Besiktas-Chelsea-striker-lands-Turkey-complete-move.html|accessdate=18 July 2014|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nBa made his official competitive debut for the club against [[Feyenoord]] in the first-leg of [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round|third qualifying round]] of the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League]], coming on as a substitute for [[O\u011fuzhan \u00d6zyakup]] in the 59th minute, as the match ended 2\u20131 for Be\u015fikta\u015f.<ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-1stgame-1\">{{cite news|title=Be\u015fikta\u015f Edge Past Feyenoord in Close Contest | url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000546/match=2014179/postmatch/lineups/index.html |publisher=[[UEFA]] | date =30 July 2014 | accessdate =30 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-1stgame-2\">{{cite news|title=Avantaj Be\u015fikta\u015f'ta! | url=http://www.mackolik.com/Haber/163677/Avantaj-Be\u015fikta\u015f'ta |publisher=mackolik.com | date = 30 July 2014 | accessdate = 30 July 2014 | language = tr}}</ref>\nIn the second-leg in Istanbul, which was the first time he was in the starting eleven, Ba scored three goals, marking his first hat-trick with the Turkish club in which ended 3\u20131.<ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-2ndgame-1\">{{cite news|title=Ba treble fires Be\u015fikta\u015f past Feyenoord | url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000546/match=2014194/index.html |publisher=[[UEFA]] | date = 6 August 2014 | accessdate = 24 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-2ndgame-2\">{{cite news|title= Champions League - Ba hat-trick fires Besiktas past Feyenoord | url=http://www.dailysabah.com/football/2014/08/08/demba-bas-hattrick-fires-besiktas-past-feyenoord |publisher=[[Sabah (newspaper)|Daily Sabah]] | date = 8 August 2014 | accessdate = 24 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-2ndgame-3\">{{cite news |title=Demba Ba's Hat-Trick Fires Be\u015fikta\u015f Past Feyenoord |url=https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/football-ba-hat-trick-fires-besiktas-celtic-humbled-221055427--sow.html |publisher=[[Eurosport]] via [[Reuters]] |date=6 August 2014 |accessdate=24 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826120557/https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/football-ba-hat-trick-fires-besiktas-celtic-humbled-221055427--sow.html |archivedate=26 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 19 August, Ba tried a straight shot right after the kick-off, which was saved by [[FC Arsenal|Arsenal]] keeper [[Wojciech Szcz\u0119sny]] at [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round#Play-off round|Play-off Round]] first leg, which ended 0\u20130.<ref name=\"ECL-Besiktas-Arsenal_1stgame-1\">{{cite news|title=Arsenal hold firm to frustrate Be\u015fikta\u015f | url= http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000547/match=2014202/postmatch/report/index.html?autoplay=true |publisher=[[UEFA]] | date = 19 August 2014 | accessdate = 24 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nBa made a great start to Turkish top flight and scored 8 times in 10 games for Besiktas over the first twelve weeks of the season. In UEFA Europa League, Ba proved to be instrumental for Besiktas' success and managed to score 5 times in 5 games while Besiktas advanced for the knockout phase.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Shanghai Shenhua===\nOn 28 June 2015, it was confirmed that Ba had signed a three-year deal with [[Chinese Super League]] club [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12691/9897267/demba-ba-has-joined-chinese-club-shanghai-shenhua-from-besiktas|title=Demba Ba has joined Chinese club Shanghai Shenhua from Besiktas|date=28 June 2015|work=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> He made his debut on 11 July, starting in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Tianjin Teda F.C.|Tianjin Teda]], and scored his first goal four days later in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Beijing Guoan]]. Ba finished the season with 6 goals in 11 games, including a hat-trick in the final game on 31 October, a 3\u20131 win over [[Jiangsu Suning F.C.|Jiangsu Sainty]], also at the [[Hongkou Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Senegalli Gol Makinesi Demba Ba, Jiangsu M\u00fccadelesinde Hat-Trick Yapt\u0131|trans-title=Senegalese goal machine Demba Ba scores a hat-trick against Jiangsu|url=http://www.90min.com/tr/posts/2689696-senegalli-gol-makinesi-demba-ba-jiangsu-mucadelesinde-hat-trick-yapti|accessdate=18 July 2016|publisher=90 Min|date=31 October 2015|language=Turkish}}</ref> Although Shanghai lost to Jiangsu Sainty in the [[2015 Chinese FA Cup]] final, Ba won the titles of 2015 Chinese FA Cup Most Valuable Player and Top Scorer.<ref name=\"CFA\">{{cite web | url = http://sports.sohu.com/20151129/n428772237.shtml | title = \u8db3\u534f\u676f\u5956\u9879\uff1a\u821c\u5929\u4e3b\u5e05\u6700\u4f73\u6559\u7ec3 \u767b\u5df4\u5df4\u8363\u81baMVP | language = zh | website = sports.sohu.com | date = 29 November 2015 | access-date = 18 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn Ba's second season at Shanghai Shenhua, he scored 14 goals in 18 Super League games, including hat-tricks in wins against [[Shijiazhuang Ever Bright F.C.|Shijiazhuang Ever Bright]] on 3 April 2016, and [[Hangzhou Greentown F.C.|Hangzhou Greentown]] on 19 June.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yue|first1=Ma|title=Ba\u2019s hat-trick fires Shenhua|url=http://www.shanghaidaily.com/sports/soccer/Bas-hattrick-fires-Shenhua/shdaily.shtml|accessdate=18 July 2016|work=Shanghai Daily|date=20 June 2016}}</ref> On 17 July, Ba broke his leg during a match against [[Shanghai SIPG F.C.|Shanghai SIPG]] when he was knocked off balance by [[Sun Xiang]] and fell with his leg twisting under him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnfc.com/chinese-super-league/story/2913756/former-chelsea-striker-demba-ba-suffers-horrific-injury-in-shanghai-derby|title=Ex-Chelsea striker Demba Ba suffers horrific injury in Shanghai derby|date=17 July 2016|work=[[ESPN FC]] | accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> Shenhua coach [[Gregorio Manzano]] stated the injury could potentially \"end his professional career.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36820635|title=Demba Ba: Ex-Chelsea & Newcastle striker suffers broken leg|date=17 July 2016|work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> French doctor Olivier Bringer performed surgery on Ba's fractured leg successfully on 22 July.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yue|first1=Ma|title=French doctor claims success in Demba Ba's surgery|url=http://www.shanghaidaily.com/sports/soccer/French-doctor-claims-success-in-Demba-Bas-surgery/shdaily.shtml|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=Shanghai Daily|date=22 July 2016}}</ref> After the operation, Bringer affirmed that Ba would be able to play football in a few months.<ref>{{cite news|title=Demba Ba can return to football 'in a few months' after leg break - surgeon|url=http://www.espnfc.com/chinese-super-league/story/2916085/demba-ba-can-return-to-football-after-leg-break-surgeon|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=ESPN|date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Turkey===\nOn 31 January 2017, [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] confirmed that Ba will join the club on loan from Shanghai Shenhua until May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjk.com.tr/tr/haber/68902/|publisher=Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|title=Yuvana Ho\u015fgeldin Demba Ba|date=31 January 2017|accessdate=31 January 2017 | language = tr}}</ref> On 31 January 2018, Ba joined Turkish S\u00fcper Lig side [[G\u00f6ztepe S.K.]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goztepe.org.tr/Haberler/futbol/demba-ba-goztepemizde/6464 |publisher=G\u00f6ztepe S.K.|title=Demba Ba G\u00f6ztepe'mizde|date=31 January 2018|accessdate=31 January 2018 | language = tr}}</ref>\n\n===Rejoin Shanghai Shenhua ===\nBa rejoined [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]] on 14 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2018-06-14/doc-ihcwpcmq9595613.shtml| title =\u7533\u82b1\u5ba3\u5e03\u767b\u5df4\u5df4\u5df2\u901a\u8fc7\u4f53\u68c0\u6b63\u5f0f\u56de\u5f52 697\u59299\u53f7\u5f52\u6765| website =Sina|date=14 June 2018| access-date = 14 June 2018}}</ref> On 18 July 2018, he made his return debut and scored the winning goal in a 1\u20130 home win over [[Tianjin TEDA F.C.|Tianjin TEDA]].<ref>{{cite web | url =http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2018-07-18/doc-ihfnsvza3517880.shtml| title =\u8679\u53e3\u4e4b\u738b\u5f52\u6765\u9001\u7edd\u6740\uff01\u7403\u8ff7\u7b49\u4e86\u4e24\u5e74 \u4ed6\u6709\u672a\u7adf\u4e4b\u68a6| website =Sina|date=18 July 2018| access-date = 19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir===\nIn January 2019, Ba terminated his contract with Shenhua by mutual consent and joined Turkish club [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2019-01-22/doc-ihqfskcn9491692.shtml | title = \u4e0a\u6d77\u7533\u82b1\u5b98\u65b9\u5ba3\u5e03\u767b\u5df4\u5df4\u79bb\u961f \u4e2a\u4eba\u539f\u56e0\u7533\u8bf7\u89e3\u7ea6 | website = Sina Sport | date = 22 January 2019 | access-date = 23 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46960766 | title = Demba Ba: Ex-Chelsea, Newcastle and West Ham striker joins Turkish Super Lig leaders Istanbul Basaksehir | website = BBC Sport | date = 22 January 2019 | access-date = 22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nBa has played a total of 17 games and scored four goals<ref name=\"Ba, Demba\"/> for [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]], the country of his parents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/nationalleagues/nationalleague=england-premier-league-2000000000/news/newsid/160/137/1/index.html|title=The entwined journeys of Ba and Cisse|date=17 March 2012|accessdate=11 April 2014|work=FIFA}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBa is a practising [[Muslim]].<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2140137/Alan-Pardew-says-religion-played-big-Newcastles-success.html |title = We must embrace religion, says Newcastle boss Pardew as he considers introducing prayer room |first = Bob |last = Cass |date = 5 May 2012 |accessdate =22 May 2012 |newspaper = Daily Mail |location = London}}</ref> He observes fasting during the Islamic month of [[Ramadan]], along with celebrating his goals by performing the [[Sujud]].<ref name=\"themag\">{{cite news |last=Smithfield|first=Jackie|url=http://www.themag.co.uk/guest-writers/ramadan-a-positive-for-cisse-ba/|title=Ramadan A Positive For Cisse and Ba?|publisher= Dadyal Online |date=24 July 2012|accessdate=30 December 2012}}</ref> On 26 June 2017, Ba co-founded with [[Eden Hazard]], [[Yohan Cabaye]] and [[Moussa Sow]], an expansion [[North American Soccer League]] franchise, [[San Diego 1904 FC]], to begin playing in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.nasl.com/news/2017/06/26/nasl-announces-expansion-club-in-san-diego-for-2018-season |title = NASL announces expansion club in San Diego for 2018 season |publisher= North American Soccer League |date = 26 June 2017 |accessdate =26 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|15 March 2020}}<ref name=\"Soccerway\">{{cite web | url = https://int.soccerway.com/players/demba-ba/13192/ | title = D. Ba | publisher = Soccerway | accessdate = 6 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season !! Club !! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n! colspan=3 | France\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Coupe de France|Coupe France]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|2005\u201306|||[[FC Rouen|Rouen]]|||[[Championnat de France amateur|CFA]]||26||22||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||22\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | France total\n!26||22||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||22\n|-\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Belgium\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Belgian Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Belgian First Division|2006\u201307]]|||[[R.E. Mouscron|Mouscron]]|||[[Belgian Pro League|Pro League]]||12||8||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||8\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Belgium total\n!12||8||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||8\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Germany\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[DFB-Pokal]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 2. Bundesliga|2007\u201308]]||rowspan=\"4\"|[[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]]|||[[2. Bundesliga]]||30||12||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||12\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Bundesliga|2008\u201309]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Bundesliga]]||33||14||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||14\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Bundesliga|2009\u201310]]||17||5||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||18||5\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Bundesliga|2010\u201311]]||17||6||3||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||20||9\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Germany total\n!97||37||6||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||103||40\n|-\n! colspan=3 | England\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[FA Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Premier League|2010\u201311]]|||[[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]||rowspan=\"5\"|[[Premier League]]||12||7||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||13||7\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]||34||16||0||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||36||16\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Premier League|2012\u201313]]||20||13||0||0||0||0||2||0||22||13\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Premier League|2012\u201313]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]||14||2||6||4||2||0||0||0||22||6\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Premier League|2013\u201314]]||19||5||1||0||3||0||6||3||29||8\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | England total\n!99||43||8||4||7||0||8||3||122||50\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Turkey\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Turkish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 S\u00fcper Lig|2014\u201315]]|||[[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]]||[[S\u00fcper Lig]]\n||29||18||3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||8||44||27\n|-\n! colspan=3 | China\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Chinese FA Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Chinese Super Cup|Super Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Asian Football Confederation|Asia]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2015 Chinese Super League|2015]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Chinese Super League]]\n||11||6||5||6||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||16||12\n|-\n|[[2016 Chinese Super League|2016]]\n||18||14||3||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||21||17\n\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | China total\n!29||20||8||9||0||0||0||0||37||29\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Turkey\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Turkish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 S\u00fcper Lig|2016\u201317]]|||[[Be\u015fikta\u015f]] (loan)||rowspan=\"2\"|[[S\u00fcper Lig]]\n||2||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||2||1\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 S\u00fcper Lig|2017\u201318]]|||[[G\u00f6ztepe S.K.|G\u00f6ztepe]]\n||13||7||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||13||7\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Turkey total\n!44||26||3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||8||59||35\n|-\n! colspan=3 | China\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Chinese FA Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Chinese Super Cup|Super Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Asian Football Confederation|Asia]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2018 Chinese Super League|2018]]||[[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]]||[[Chinese Super League]]\n||17||5||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||17||5\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Turkey\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Turkish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 S\u00fcper Lig|2018\u201319]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|S\u00fcper Lig\n|5||2||0||0||0||0||0||0||5||2\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 \u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K. season|2019\u201320]]\n|20||10||4||2||0||0||6||0||30||12\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Total\n!25||12||4||2||0||0||6||0||35||14\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Career totals\n!338||170||29||19||7||0||26||11||400||200\n|}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|29 March 2015}}<ref name=\"Ba, Demba\">{{NFT player|id=22847|name=Ba, Demba|accessdate=5 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! National team !! Year !! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"9\" valign=\"center\"|[[Senegal national football team|Senegal]]\n| 2007 || 5 || 1\n|-\n| 2008 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 2009 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2010 || 2 || 1\n|-\n| 2011 || 2 || 1\n|-\n| 2012 || 5 || 1\n|-\n| 2013 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| 2014 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| 2015 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total !! 19 !! 4\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Be\u015fikta\u015f'''\n*[[S\u00fcper Lig]]: [[2016\u201317 S\u00fcper Lig|2016\u201317]]{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Premier League Player of the Month]]: [[2011\u201312 Premier League#Monthly awards|December 2011]]<ref name=PremProfile/>\n*[[Chinese FA Cup]] Most Valuable Player: [[2015 Chinese FA Cup#Awards|2015]]<ref name=\"CFA\"/>\n*[[Chinese Super League]] Team of the Year: [[2016 Chinese Super League#Awards|2016]]{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{NFT player}}\n* {{Soccerway}}\n* {{FIFA player}}\n* {{UEFA player}}\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{ESPN FC}}\n* {{Fussballdaten}}\n\n{{\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K. squad}}\n{{Senegal squad 2012 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{2016 Chinese Super League Team of the Year}}\n{{Chinese FA Cup top scorers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ba, Demba}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French people of Senegalese descent]]\n[[Category:People from S\u00e8vres]]\n[[Category:French Muslims]]\n[[Category:Senegalese Muslims]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hauts-de-Seine]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:Senegalese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:FC Rouen players]]\n[[Category:R.E. Mouscron players]]\n[[Category:TSG 1899 Hoffenheim players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K. footballers]]\n[[Category:Shanghai Shenhua F.C. players]]\n[[Category:G\u00f6ztepe S.K. footballers]]\n[[Category:\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K. players]]\n[[Category:Championnat National 2 players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:S\u00fcper Lig players]]\n[[Category:Chinese Super League players]]\n[[Category:Senegal international footballers]]\n[[Category:2012 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:French expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|association football player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Demba Ba\n| image          = Demba_Ba_BJK'14.JPG\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Ba playing for [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] in 2014\n| fullname       = Demba Ba<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tff.org/Default.aspx?pageId=526&kisiId=1721847 |title=Demba Ba |publisher=Turkish Football Federation |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1985|5|25|df=y}}<ref>{{Hugman|22147|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place    = [[S\u00e8vres]], France\n| height         = 1.89 m<ref name=PremProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/4213/Demba-Ba/overview |title=Demba Ba: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub    = [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]]\n| clubnumber     = 19\n| youthyears1    = 1999\u20132000 |youthclubs1 = Port Autonome\n| youthyears2    = 2000\u20132001 |youthclubs2 = Frileuse\n| youthyears3    = 2001\u20132004 |youthclubs3 = Montrouge\n| years1         = 2005\u20132006 |clubs1 = [[FC Rouen|Rouen]]                          |caps1 = 26 |goals1 = 22\n| years2         = 2006\u20132007 |clubs2 = [[R.E. Mouscron|Mouscron]]                  |caps2 = 12 |goals2 = 8\n| years3         = 2007\u20132011 |clubs3 = [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]]     |caps3 = 97 |goals3 = 37\n| years4         = 2011       |clubs4 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]   |caps4 = 12 |goals4 = 7\n| years5         = 2011\u20132013 |clubs5 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]  |caps5 = 54 |goals5 = 29\n| years6         = 2013\u20132014 |clubs6 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]                    |caps6 = 33 |goals6 = 7\n| years7         = 2014\u20132015 |clubs7 = [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]]                  |caps7 = 29 |goals7 = 18\n| years8         = 2015\u20132018 |clubs8 = [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]]  |caps8 = 29 |goals8 = 20\n| years9         = 2017       |clubs9 = \u2192 [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] (loan)         |caps9 = 2  |goals9 = 1\n| years10        = 2018       |clubs10 = [[G\u00f6ztepe S.K.|G\u00f6ztepe]]                   |caps10 = 13  |goals10 = 7\n| years11        = 2018\u20132019     |clubs11= [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]]  |caps11 = 17 |goals11 = 5\n| years12        = 2019\u2013       |clubs12 = [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]]      |caps12 = 25  |goals12 = 12\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 19\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| pcupdate       = 18:59, 15 March 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate       = 29 March 2015\n}}\n'''Demba Ba''' (born 25 May 1985) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for Turkish club [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]] and the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]].\n\nHe made his first-team debut with French team [[FC Rouen|Rouen]] in 2005 before moving to [[R.E. Mouscron|Mouscron]] and onto [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]] in Germany in 2007. In 2011, he moved to [[Premier League]] side [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. He played only 12 games for West Ham and despite being their league top goal scorer in the 2010\u201311 season, they were relegated to the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] and Ba moved to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]. In January 2013, he completed a move to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] for an undisclosed fee, before joining [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] for \u20ac6 million 18 months later. After one season in Turkey, he moved to [[Shanghai Shenhua]] of the [[Chinese Super League]].\n\nBorn and raised in France, Ba has been a full international for Senegal since 2007 and represented the country at the [[2012 Africa Cup of Nations]].\n\n==Early career==\nBa was born in [[S\u00e8vres]], Hauts-de-Seine<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/demba-ba_prs173421/person.shtml |title=Demba Ba |publisher=Eurosport |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> and is the sixth child of seven. He grew up in [[Saint-Valery-en-Caux]], Seine-Maritime. He joined the youth section of ES Mont-Gaillard, located in [[Le Havre]], in 1992, before playing for Port Autonome between 1999 and 2000, and then for Frileuse between 2000 and 2001.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.demba-ba.eu/biography.html|title=Biography of Demba Ba|publisher= Demba Ba official website|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Ba returned to [[Ch\u00e2tillon, Hauts-de-Seine|Ch\u00e2tillon]] and played for Montrouge.<ref name=\"Bio\"/> He played there until 2004, at which point he decided to concentrate on his football.<ref name=\"Bio\"/> Later that year, after unsuccessful trials at [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] and [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]],<ref name=\"Bio\"/> Ba moved to the United Kingdom to seek a professional contract. He was recommended to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] manager [[Ray Lewington]] through his friend [[Gauthier Diafutua]], then a Watford player, but released shortly after Lewington's dismissal. Ba then spent a week on trial at [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]],<ref name=\"Bio\"/> and returned to France after two more unsuccessful trials at Football League sides [[Swansea City]] and [[Gillingham FC|Gillingham]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/20891896 | title = Demba Ba: Barnsley rejection to Chelsea transfer talks | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 2 January 2013 | accessdate = 12 December 2013 | first = Gary | last = Rose}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Rouen===\nBa signed with manager Alain Michel because they were both moving to French club [[FC Rouen|Rouen]] on a one-year contract, and Ba enjoyed a highly successful season with the club.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Mouscron===\nBelgian club [[R.E. Mouscron|Mouscron]] beat off competition from numerous other clubs to win Ba's signature in 2006. Scoring in each of his first three games, he then picked up fractures in his tibia and fibula, and was out of action between August 2006 and April 2007. Following his eight-month recovery period he scored seven goals in nine games, and picked up his first international cap.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===1899 Hoffenheim===\n[[File:Demba Ba Sinsheim.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Ba, pictured in 2009]]\n\nOn 29 August 2007, Ba moved to [[2. Bundesliga]] side [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]] for \u20ac3&nbsp;million. Ba was an integral part of Hoffenheim's [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the [[Bundesliga]] and their successful first season in the Bundesliga, where they finished seventh after leading during the [[Christmas]] break. In that season he scored 14 goals, only missing one game all season. These goals included a hat-trick in a 3\u20133 game against [[VfB Stuttgart|Stuttgart]] on 24 February 2009. In all competitions Ba scored 40 goals in 103 appearances for TSG 1899 Hoffenheim.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tsg-hoffenheim.de/4news.php?d%5Bnr%5D=1950&d%5Babteilung%5D=Startseite |title=1899 Hoffenheim signs Carlos Eduardo and Demba Ba |publisher=TSG 1899 Hoffenheim |accessdate=29 August 2007 |language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927050052/http://www.tsg-hoffenheim.de/4news.php?d%5Bnr%5D=1950&d%5Babteilung%5D=Startseite |archivedate=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\nIn July 2009, he was due to move to [[VfB Stuttgart]], but the move fell through after he failed a medical.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite.html/511232/artikel_Ba-muss-bei-1899-bleiben.html|title=Stuttgart ist das Risiko zu gro\u00df|work=kicker|accessdate=15 January 2011|date=9 July 2009|language=German|trans-title=Stuttgart thinks the risk is too great}}</ref> In December of that year Ba extended his contract at Hoffenheim to 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://achtzehn99.de/obasi-ba-und-compper-verl-ngern-vertr-ge-vorzeitig/ | title = Obasi, Ba und Compper verl\u00e4ngern Vertr\u00e4ge vorzeitig | language = German | date = 16 December 2009 | publisher = TSG 1899 Hoffenheim | accessdate =16 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Move to England====\nBa left Hoffenheim for disputed reasons in January 2011. Claiming the club had gone back on an agreed transfer to a [[Premier League]] club, believed to be [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], he refused to travel to Hoffenheim's winter training camp. In response, Hoffenheim's general manager said his contract would be cancelled, he would face legal action, and he would be fined and prevented from moving to another club for six months.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/9344952.stm | title = Hoffenheim refuse to release Senegal's Demba Ba | publisher = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 6 January 2011 | accessdate =5 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.demba-ba.eu/newsreader-en/items/explanation-from-demba.html|title=Explanation from Demba|publisher=Demba Ba official website|accessdate=6 January 2011|date=6 January 2011}}</ref> The club also later claimed he travelled to England without permission in order to force a move, which they reluctantly agreed needs to happen due to Ba's actions.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/7333438/Hoffenheim-No-Ba-regrets | title = Hoffenheim&nbsp;\u2013 No Ba regrets | first = Thomas | last = Zocher | publisher = Sky Sports | date = 25 November 2011 | accessdate =10 December 2011}}</ref> The club later agreed to a transfer to [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] for a reported fee of \u00a37.1 million, but it fell through after Ba had agreed personal terms but failed his medical for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11661/6661259/ | title = Stoke step up Ba pursuit | publisher = Sky Sports | date = 14 January 2011 | accessdate =10 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11701/6664487/ | title = Ba's Stoke move breaks downl | publisher = Sky Sports | date = 15 January 2011 | accessdate =10 December 2011}}</ref> Expressing disappointment, Stoke City manager [[Tony Pulis]] said \"Obviously they found something which could cause problems later\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/6665036/ | title = Pulis upset over Ba deal | first = Hayley | last = Paterson | publisher = Sky Sports | date = 15 January 2011 | accessdate =10 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving Hoffenheim, the club's general manager Ernst Tanner stated the club stand by their decision selling Ba.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hoffenheim \u2013 No Ba regrets|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11678/7333438/hoffenheim-no-ba-regrets|publisher=Sky Sports|date=25 November 2011|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===West Ham United===\n[[File:DembaBa.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Ba with West Ham United in 2011]]\n\nAfter the collapsed Stoke deal, Ba was sold to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] for an undisclosed fee based on appearances. He signed a three-year contract on 28 January, on a pay as you play basis due to knee problems found in the Stoke medical.<ref name=\"guardian_2011-06-15\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jun/15/demba-ba-west-ham-everton | title = Demba Ba leaves West Ham and looks to the Premier League | newspaper = The Guardian | location = London | first = Jamie | last = Jackson | accessdate =5 January 2012 | date = 15 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.whufc.com/articles/20110128/hammers-capture-ba_2236884_2275381|title=Hammers capture Ba|publisher=West Ham United F.C|accessdate=28 January 2011|date=28 January 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110131054335/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20110128/hammers-capture-ba_2236884_2275381|archivedate=31 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stoke_city/9361494.stm|title=Hoffenheim striker Demba Ba fails Stoke City medical |publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 January 2011|date=15 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_ham_utd/9371608.stm|title=West Ham sign Senegal striker Demba Ba until 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 January 2011|date=28 January 2011}}</ref> Ba's Premier League debut came on 6 February 2011, as a 75th-minute substitute for [[Robbie Keane]] during a 1\u20130 home defeat by [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9385585.stm|title=West Ham 0&nbsp;\u2013 1 Birmingham |publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 February 2011|date=6 February 2011}}</ref> His first goals followed six days later during his full debut, scoring twice in a 3\u20133 draw against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9391009.stm|title=West Brom 3 \u2013 3 West Ham|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=13 February 2011|date=12 February 2011}}</ref> Despite finishing as their top scorer for the season with seven from twelve games including 2 in the last game, Ba's stay with West Ham proved to be short.<ref name=\"BA2010-11\">{{cite web | url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2802#teamTabs=stats | title=West Ham Stats 2010\u201311 | publisher=Soccerbase | accessdate=13 June 2011}}</ref> Following their relegation to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]] after a 3\u20132 loss away to [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] he invoked a release clause in his contract allowing him to leave for free. He turned down a \u00a350,000-a-week salary plus a bonus payment of \u00a3500,000 in order to stay in the Premier League with another club, triggering interest from both [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref name=\"guardian_2011-06-15\" /><ref name=\"Barelegation\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9484432.stm | title=Wigan 3\u20132 West Ham | publisher=BBC Sport | date= 15 May 2011 | accessdate=13 June 2011 | last =McNulty | first = Phil}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\n====2011\u201312 season====\nOn 17 June 2011, Ba signed for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on a three-year deal, making his club debut on 13 August 2011 in the 0\u20130 draw against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nufc.co.uk/articles/20110617/ba-seals-united-move_2281670_2377974|title=Ba Seals United Move|publisher=Newcastle United F.C|accessdate=17 June 2011|date=17 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/14429552.stm|title=Newcastle 0\u20130 Arsenal|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 September 2011|date=13 August 2011}}</ref> His first goals for the club came on 24 September 2011 with a [[List of Premier League hat-tricks|hat-trick]] against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in a 3\u20131 home win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/14958133.stm |title=Newcastle 3 \u2013 1 Blackburn|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 September 2011|date=24 September 2011}}</ref> A second hat-trick came in a 3\u20131 away win at Stoke City, taking his league total to 8 and maintaining the club's 11 game unbeaten league start, taking them to 3rd in the league.<ref>{{cite news|last=Magowan|first=Alistair|title=Stoke 1 \u2013 3 Newcastle |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15425921.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=31 October 2011|date=31 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story/_/id/977793/richard-jolly:-newcastle's-lasting-impression?cc=5901 |title=Richard Jolly: Newcastle's lasting impression | publisher = ESPN Soccernet |date=31 October 2011 |accessdate=3 November 2011 |first = Richard | last = Jolly}}</ref> Ba's goalscoring form continued despite Newcastle entering a downward spell, and saw him picked in ESPN.com's Premier League Best XI for the first half of the season, and named [[Premier League Player of the Month]] for December 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/columnist/hirshey_david/id/7379143/all-prem-team-far-david-hirshey-james-tyler|title=ESPN.com's all-Prem team (so far)|date=23 December 2011|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=318012&cc=5901 | title = Baggies extend Toon's winless run | publisher = ESPN Soccernet | date = 21 December 2011 | accessdate =4 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/16173188.stm | title = Newcastle 2 \u2013 3 West Brom | first = Saj | last = Chowdhury | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 21 December 2011 | accessdate =4 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy the time Ba left to play in the January [[2012 Africa Cup of Nations]] his league tally had reached 15, making him second top scorer in the league behind Arsenal's [[Robin van Persie]]. He left for the tournament on a high note, scoring the first in a 3\u20130 home win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 4 January 2012, the team's first victory against the league champions in over a decade.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16343415.stm | title = Newcastle 3 \u2013 0 Man Utd | publisher = BBC Sport | accessdate =5 January 2012 | date = 4 January 2012 | first = Saj | last = Chowdhury}}</ref> While at the Africa Cup of Nations tournament, Ba's Senegal teammate [[Papiss Ciss\u00e9]] also signed for Newcastle.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nufc.co.uk/articles/20120117/newcastle-sign-papiss-cisse_2281670_2580079 | title = Newcastle Sign Papiss Cisse | accessdate =17 January 2012 | publisher = Newcastle United F.C}}</ref> Ba and Ciss\u00e9 returned earlier than expected after Senegal finished bottom of their group, with Ba having missed three Premier League games and two [[2011\u201312 FA Cup|FA Cup]] games, the second of which saw Newcastle knocked out of the cup.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16750126.stm | title=Newcastle's Demba Ba & Demba Cisse to return early from Africa | work=BBC News}}</ref> He returned to action against Aston Villa on their visit to St James' Park on 5 February 2012, his return proved to be a goal scoring one as he netted the opener in the game which Newcastle won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/feb/05/newcastle-united-aston-villa-premier-league | title = Newcastle's 'Double Demba' prove too hot for Aston Villa to handle | newspaper = The Guardian | location = London | date = 5 February 2012 | accessdate =20 March 2012 | first = Louise | last = Taylor}}</ref> This would prove to be Ba's last goal of the season, as he moved to the left of a three pronged attack with Papiss Ciss\u00e9 leading the line, and grabbing 12 goals in the second half of the season. Despite this late season slump, Ba was voted as the best signing of the 2011\u201312 season by Premier League managers in March 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nufc.co.uk/articles/20120314/demba-voted-best-signing_2281670_2658261 | title = Demba Voted Best Signing | publisher = Newcastle United F.C | accessdate = 20 March 2012 | first = Anthony | last = Marshall | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120315160324/http://www.nufc.co.uk/articles/20120314/demba-voted-best-signing_2281670_2658261 | archivedate = 15 March 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He finished the season as Newcastle's leading goal scorer, with 16 goals.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nBa got his season off to a strong start scoring in a 1\u20130 win against [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]], in Landsberg am Lech, Germany on 16 July 2012. He also scored in a 2\u20131 win against [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] which helped Newcastle win the [[Guadiana Trophy]]. In Newcastle's first league game against Tottenham, Ba opened the scoring with a fantastic volleyed effort in a 2\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/261565/report |title=Losing start for Villas-Boas |publisher=Sky Sports |date=18 August 2012}}</ref> On 17 September 2012, he scored Newcastle's 1000th goal of the [[Premier League]] era, after scoring both goals in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Goodison Park]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19540636 | title = Everton 2\u20132 Newcastle | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 17 September 2012 | accessdate = 17 September 2012}}</ref> On 29 September, he scored for the third game in a row as he scored twice in a 2\u20132 draw away to [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], the first a volley, the second however proved controversial as the ball struck his arm before going in.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19684438 | title = Reading 2\u20132 Newcastle | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 29 September 2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was known that Ba had a release clause in his contract valued at \u00a37 million causing speculation of him making a transfer to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/9772105/Chelseas-move-for-Demba-Ba-stalls-over-Newcastle-players-wage-demands.html | title = Chelsea's move for Demba Ba stalls | newspaper = The Daily Telegraph | location = London | date = 31 December 2012 | accessdate = 3 January 2013 | first2 = Luke | last2 = Edwards | first1 = Chris | last1 =  Bascombe}}</ref> This speculation was confirmed by Newcastle manager [[Alan Pardew]] on 2 January 2013 who said that the transfer was \"done\" and Ba would \"go to Chelsea with our blessing.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/9776978/Demba-Ba-heading-to-Chelsea-from-Newcastle-as-70000-a-week-deal-breaks-transfer-deadlock.html | title = Demba Ba heading to Chelsea from Newcastle as \u00a370,000-a-week deal breaks transfer deadlock | newspaper = The Daily Telegraph | location = London | date = 2 January 2013 | accessdate = 3 January 2013 | first = Luke | last = Edwards}}</ref>\n\n===Chelsea===\n[[File:Chelsea FC v Paris Saint-Germain, 8 April 2014 (56).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Ba playing for Chelsea in 2014]]\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nOn 4 January 2013, Ba joined Chelsea for an undisclosed fee. Ba signed a three-and-a-half-year contract, becoming the first ever Senegalese player to join the club. He received the vacant number 29 shirt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ba transfer completed |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3030470/title/ba-transfer-completed |publisher=Chelsea F.C |date=4 January 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105020148/http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3030470/title/ba-transfer-completed |archivedate=5 January 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\nBa made his debut against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in the third round of the [[2012\u201313 FA Cup|FA Cup]] on 5 January. He marked his first appearance for the club by scoring two goals in a 5\u20131 victory for Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jan/05/southampton-chelsea-fa-cup |title=Chelsea's Demba Ba scores two on his debut in rout at Southampton |publisher=The Guardian |date=5 January 2013 |location=London |first=Sachin |last=Nakrani}}</ref> He scored on his home league debut on 16 January in the 2\u20132 draw against the same club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2263502/Chelsea-2-Southampton-2-match-report--More-woe-Rafa-Benitez.html |title=Chelsea 2 Southampton 2: Who can Pep up Blues? Not Rafa, say angry fans after draw  |publisher=Daily Mail |date=16 January 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 February 2013, Ba first played his former team Newcastle in a Premier League match at St. James' Park. In the 32nd minute of the match Ba had a chance to open the scoring but his initial attempt on goal was saved by Newcastle keeper [[Tim Krul]]. Ba managed to head the rebounded ball and in doing so collided with Coloccini. The collision resulted in a broken nose and Ba was substituted in the 43rd minute. Newcastle went on to win the game 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21209228 | title =  Newcastle 3 \u2013 2 Chelsea | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 2 February 2013 | accessdate = 6 February 2013}}</ref> After a run of seven games without scoring, Ba scored in a 1\u20130 win against West Bromwich Albion at Stamford Bridge on 2 March.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21556758 |title=Chelsea interim manager Rafael Benitez ended a turbulent week with the satisfaction of victory as West Bromwich Albion were beaten at Stamford Bridge |publisher=BBC Sport | date=2 March 2013 | accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref> On 1 April, Ba scored a goal from a long [[Juan Mata]] cross in the FA Cup quarter-final replay against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], giving Chelsea a 1\u20130 victory and a spot at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the semi-finals of the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/chelsea-1-0-manchester-united-match-1796483|title=Chelsea 1\u20130 Man United: Unforgettable Ba strike settles rather forgettable FA Cup replay |work=Daily Mirror |date=1 April 2013| accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> He was cup-tied for Chelsea's victorious [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/demba-ba-winning-cups-means-more-than-top-four-finish-8580088.html |title=Demba Ba: Winning cups means more than top-four finish |publisher=Standard |date=19 April 2013 |accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\n[[File:Demba ba chelsea.JPG|thumb|Ba training with Chelsea before a [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] match]]\n\nFor the [[2013\u201314 Chelsea F.C. season|2013\u201314 season]], Ba's squad number was switched from 29 to 19, his squad number while at [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle]]. In the summer transfer window, Ba was subjected of a transfer bid from his former clubs Newcastle United,<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer news: Sky sources: Newcastle keen to re-sign Demba Ba from Chelsea|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8893259/transfer-news-sky-sources-newcastle-keen-to-re-sign-demba-ba-from-chelsea|publisher=Sky Sports|date=28 August 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> West Ham United<ref>{{cite news|title=West Ham boss Sam Allardyce sets sights on Demba Ba|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/sport/football/332354/West-Ham-boss-Sam-Allardyce-sets-sights-on-Demba-Ba|publisher=Daily Star|date=14 August 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Ba was on the verge of joining Arsenal on a season-long loan, but the move fell through.<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer Deadline Day: Demba Ba not going to Arsenal according to Sky sources|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8903615/transfer-deadline-day-demba-ba-not-going-to-arsenal-according-to-sky-sources|publisher=Sky Sports|date=3 September 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> It was later revealed that the move fell through thanks to Chelsea intervention,<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea block Arsenal Demba Ba move as Blues boss Jose Mourinho sees Arsene Wenger's men as title rivals|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/demba-bas-move-arsenal-blocked-2246401?|work=Daily Mirror|date=2 September 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> though Ba himself considered moving to Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Demba Ba focused on Chelsea future after Arsenal interest|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24131190|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 September 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe scored his first goal of the season after coming on as a substitute in [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] match against [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke]] in a 3\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71808#matchReport |title=MATCH REPORT: CHELSEA 3 SCHALKE 0 |publisher=Chelsea FC |date=6 November 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101160233/http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71808 |archivedate=1 January 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Ba's first [[2013\u201314 Premier League|Premier League]] goal of the season sealed Chelsea's 3\u20131 victory over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71170#matchReport |title=MATCH REPORT: CHELSEA 3 SOUTHAMPTON 1 |publisher=Chelsea FC |date=1 December 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214041552/http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71170 |archivedate=14 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> He made his first Champions League start on 11 December 2013 and he scored the only goal of the game, as Chelsea won 1\u20130 against [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71811#matchReport |title=MATCH REPORT: CHELSEA 1 STEAUA BUCHAREST 0 |publisher=Chelsea FC |date=11 December 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213012121/http://www.chelseafc.com/matchday-live/match/71811#matchReport |archivedate=13 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> On 8 March 2014, he scored twice after coming on as a 76th-minute substitute in a 4\u20130 win over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26396251|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Chelsea 4\u20130 Tottenham Hotspur |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=8 March 2014|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 2014, Ba scored an 87th-minute goal in the Champions League quarter-final second-leg against [[Paris Saint-Germain]] to send Chelsea through to the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26914647 | title =  Chelsea 2\u20130 Paris St-Germain | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 8 April 2014 | accessdate = 9 April 2014 | first = Phil | last = McNulty}}</ref> On 13 April, he scored the winning goal as Chelsea won 1\u20130 at [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26908679|title=Swansea 0\u20131 Chelsea|date=13 April 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> On 27 April, during Chelsea's third final match against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], Ba scored and Chelsea won the game 2\u20130, helping them to stay in the race for the Premier League title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebiglead.com/2014/04/27/steven-gerrards-slip-gifted-demba-ba-a-crucial-goal-in-the-epl-title-race/|title=Gerrard slip gives Chelsea goal|date=27 April 2014 | accessdate = 27 April 2014}}</ref> Having only scored 14 goals since his arrival in January 2013, Ba fell behind fellow strikers [[Samuel Eto'o]] and [[Fernando Torres]], having spent most of the season being on the sidelines.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea striker Demba Ba happy with performance in 3\u20131 win over Norwich|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8962816/chelsea-striker-demba-ba-happy-with-performance-in-3-1-win-over-norwich|publisher=Sky Sports|date=7 October 2013|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> After the arrival of [[Diego Costa]] in the summer, Chelsea decided to allow Ba to search for a new club despite his intention to stay for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfer news: Demba Ba expects to still be at Chelsea next season|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/9322604/transfer-news-demba-ba-expects-to-still-be-at-chelsea-next-season|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=23 May 2014|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Be\u015fikta\u015f===\n[[File:Demba Ba - John Terry.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Ba with former teammate [[John Terry]] in 2014]]\n\nOn 16 July 2014, [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.]] of the Turkish [[S\u00fcper Lig]] signed Ba from Chelsea for \u20ac6 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kap.gov.tr/bildirim-sorgulari/bildirim-detayi.aspx?id=371845|title=Demba Ba'n\u0131n transferine ili\u015fkin olarak Chelsea kul\u00fcb\u00fc ile anla\u015fmaya var\u0131lm\u0131\u015ft\u0131r|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=18 July 2014| language = tr}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ba moves to Besiktas|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2014/07/ba-moves-to-besiktas.html|work=[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea.com]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=18 July 2014}}</ref> He was given the number 9 shirt.<ref name=nine>{{cite news|last=Kent|first=David|title=Demba Ba will wear No 9 shirt at Besiktas after completing his move from Chelsea|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2694288/Demba-Ba-tweets-Im-Besiktas-Chelsea-striker-lands-Turkey-complete-move.html|accessdate=18 July 2014|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nBa made his official competitive debut for the club against [[Feyenoord]] in the first-leg of [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round|third qualifying round]] of the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League]], coming on as a substitute for [[O\u011fuzhan \u00d6zyakup]] in the 59th minute, as the match ended 2\u20131 for Be\u015fikta\u015f.<ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-1stgame-1\">{{cite news|title=Be\u015fikta\u015f Edge Past Feyenoord in Close Contest | url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000546/match=2014179/postmatch/lineups/index.html |publisher=[[UEFA]] | date =30 July 2014 | accessdate =30 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-1stgame-2\">{{cite news|title=Avantaj Be\u015fikta\u015f'ta! | url=http://www.mackolik.com/Haber/163677/Avantaj-Be\u015fikta\u015f'ta |publisher=mackolik.com | date = 30 July 2014 | accessdate = 30 July 2014 | language = tr}}</ref>\nIn the second-leg in Istanbul, which was the first time he was in the starting eleven, Ba scored three goals, marking his first hat-trick with the Turkish club in which ended 3\u20131.<ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-2ndgame-1\">{{cite news|title=Ba treble fires Be\u015fikta\u015f past Feyenoord | url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000546/match=2014194/index.html |publisher=[[UEFA]] | date = 6 August 2014 | accessdate = 24 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-2ndgame-2\">{{cite news|title= Champions League - Ba hat-trick fires Besiktas past Feyenoord | url=http://www.dailysabah.com/football/2014/08/08/demba-bas-hattrick-fires-besiktas-past-feyenoord |publisher=[[Sabah (newspaper)|Daily Sabah]] | date = 8 August 2014 | accessdate = 24 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ECL-Feyenoord-BJK-2ndgame-3\">{{cite news |title=Demba Ba's Hat-Trick Fires Be\u015fikta\u015f Past Feyenoord |url=https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/football-ba-hat-trick-fires-besiktas-celtic-humbled-221055427--sow.html |publisher=[[Eurosport]] via [[Reuters]] |date=6 August 2014 |accessdate=24 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826120557/https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/football-ba-hat-trick-fires-besiktas-celtic-humbled-221055427--sow.html |archivedate=26 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 19 August, Ba tried a straight shot right after the kick-off, which was saved by [[FC Arsenal|Arsenal]] keeper [[Wojciech Szcz\u0119sny]] at [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round#Play-off round|Play-off Round]] first leg, which ended 0\u20130.<ref name=\"ECL-Besiktas-Arsenal_1stgame-1\">{{cite news|title=Arsenal hold firm to frustrate Be\u015fikta\u015f | url= http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000547/match=2014202/postmatch/report/index.html?autoplay=true |publisher=[[UEFA]] | date = 19 August 2014 | accessdate = 24 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nBa made a great start to Turkish top flight and scored 8 times in 10 games for Besiktas over the first twelve weeks of the season. In UEFA Europa League, Ba proved to be instrumental for Besiktas' success and managed to score 5 times in 5 games while Besiktas advanced for the knockout phase.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Shanghai Shenhua===\nOn 28 June 2015, it was confirmed that Ba had signed a three-year deal with [[Chinese Super League]] club [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12691/9897267/demba-ba-has-joined-chinese-club-shanghai-shenhua-from-besiktas|title=Demba Ba has joined Chinese club Shanghai Shenhua from Besiktas|date=28 June 2015|work=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> He made his debut on 11 July, starting in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Tianjin Teda F.C.|Tianjin Teda]], and scored his first goal four days later in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Beijing Guoan]]. Ba finished the season with 6 goals in 11 games, including a hat-trick in the final game on 31 October, a 3\u20131 win over [[Jiangsu Suning F.C.|Jiangsu Sainty]], also at the [[Hongkou Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Senegalli Gol Makinesi Demba Ba, Jiangsu M\u00fccadelesinde Hat-Trick Yapt\u0131|trans-title=Senegalese goal machine Demba Ba scores a hat-trick against Jiangsu|url=http://www.90min.com/tr/posts/2689696-senegalli-gol-makinesi-demba-ba-jiangsu-mucadelesinde-hat-trick-yapti|accessdate=18 July 2016|publisher=90 Min|date=31 October 2015|language=Turkish}}</ref> Although Shanghai lost to Jiangsu Sainty in the [[2015 Chinese FA Cup]] final, Ba won the titles of 2015 Chinese FA Cup Most Valuable Player and Top Scorer.<ref name=\"CFA\">{{cite web | url = http://sports.sohu.com/20151129/n428772237.shtml | title = \u8db3\u534f\u676f\u5956\u9879\uff1a\u821c\u5929\u4e3b\u5e05\u6700\u4f73\u6559\u7ec3 \u767b\u5df4\u5df4\u8363\u81baMVP | language = zh | website = sports.sohu.com | date = 29 November 2015 | access-date = 18 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn Ba's second season at Shanghai Shenhua, he scored 14 goals in 18 Super League games, including hat-tricks in wins against [[Shijiazhuang Ever Bright F.C.|Shijiazhuang Ever Bright]] on 3 April 2016, and [[Hangzhou Greentown F.C.|Hangzhou Greentown]] on 19 June.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yue|first1=Ma|title=Ba\u2019s hat-trick fires Shenhua|url=http://www.shanghaidaily.com/sports/soccer/Bas-hattrick-fires-Shenhua/shdaily.shtml|accessdate=18 July 2016|work=Shanghai Daily|date=20 June 2016}}</ref> On 17 July, Ba broke his leg during a match against [[Shanghai SIPG F.C.|Shanghai SIPG]] when he was knocked off balance by [[Sun Xiang]] and fell with his leg twisting under him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnfc.com/chinese-super-league/story/2913756/former-chelsea-striker-demba-ba-suffers-horrific-injury-in-shanghai-derby|title=Ex-Chelsea striker Demba Ba suffers horrific injury in Shanghai derby|date=17 July 2016|work=[[ESPN FC]] | accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> Shenhua coach [[Gregorio Manzano]] stated the injury could potentially \"end his professional career.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36820635|title=Demba Ba: Ex-Chelsea & Newcastle striker suffers broken leg|date=17 July 2016|work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> French doctor Olivier Bringer performed surgery on Ba's fractured leg successfully on 22 July.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yue|first1=Ma|title=French doctor claims success in Demba Ba's surgery|url=http://www.shanghaidaily.com/sports/soccer/French-doctor-claims-success-in-Demba-Bas-surgery/shdaily.shtml|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=Shanghai Daily|date=22 July 2016}}</ref> After the operation, Bringer affirmed that Ba would be able to play football in a few months.<ref>{{cite news|title=Demba Ba can return to football 'in a few months' after leg break - surgeon|url=http://www.espnfc.com/chinese-super-league/story/2916085/demba-ba-can-return-to-football-after-leg-break-surgeon|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=ESPN|date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Turkey===\nOn 31 January 2017, [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] confirmed that Ba will join the club on loan from Shanghai Shenhua until May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjk.com.tr/tr/haber/68902/|publisher=Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|title=Yuvana Ho\u015fgeldin Demba Ba|date=31 January 2017|accessdate=31 January 2017 | language = tr}}</ref> On 31 January 2018, Ba joined Turkish S\u00fcper Lig side [[G\u00f6ztepe S.K.]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goztepe.org.tr/Haberler/futbol/demba-ba-goztepemizde/6464 |publisher=G\u00f6ztepe S.K.|title=Demba Ba G\u00f6ztepe'mizde|date=31 January 2018|accessdate=31 January 2018 | language = tr}}</ref>\n\n===Rejoin Shanghai Shenhua ===\nBa rejoined [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]] on 14 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2018-06-14/doc-ihcwpcmq9595613.shtml| title =\u7533\u82b1\u5ba3\u5e03\u767b\u5df4\u5df4\u5df2\u901a\u8fc7\u4f53\u68c0\u6b63\u5f0f\u56de\u5f52 697\u59299\u53f7\u5f52\u6765| website =Sina|date=14 June 2018| access-date = 14 June 2018}}</ref> On 18 July 2018, he made his return debut and scored the winning goal in a 1\u20130 home win over [[Tianjin TEDA F.C.|Tianjin TEDA]].<ref>{{cite web | url =http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2018-07-18/doc-ihfnsvza3517880.shtml| title =\u8679\u53e3\u4e4b\u738b\u5f52\u6765\u9001\u7edd\u6740\uff01\u7403\u8ff7\u7b49\u4e86\u4e24\u5e74 \u4ed6\u6709\u672a\u7adf\u4e4b\u68a6| website =Sina|date=18 July 2018| access-date = 19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir===\nIn January 2019, Ba terminated his contract with Shenhua by mutual consent and joined Turkish club [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2019-01-22/doc-ihqfskcn9491692.shtml | title = \u4e0a\u6d77\u7533\u82b1\u5b98\u65b9\u5ba3\u5e03\u767b\u5df4\u5df4\u79bb\u961f \u4e2a\u4eba\u539f\u56e0\u7533\u8bf7\u89e3\u7ea6 | website = Sina Sport | date = 22 January 2019 | access-date = 23 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46960766 | title = Demba Ba: Ex-Chelsea, Newcastle and West Ham striker joins Turkish Super Lig leaders Istanbul Basaksehir | website = BBC Sport | date = 22 January 2019 | access-date = 22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nBa has played a total of 17 games and scored four goals<ref name=\"Ba, Demba\"/> for [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]], the country of his parents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/nationalleagues/nationalleague=england-premier-league-2000000000/news/newsid/160/137/1/index.html|title=The entwined journeys of Ba and Cisse|date=17 March 2012|accessdate=11 April 2014|work=FIFA}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBa is a practising [[Muslim]].<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2140137/Alan-Pardew-says-religion-played-big-Newcastles-success.html |title = We must embrace religion, says Newcastle boss Pardew as he considers introducing prayer room |first = Bob |last = Cass |date = 5 May 2012 |accessdate =22 May 2012 |newspaper = Daily Mail |location = London}}</ref> He observes fasting during the Islamic month of [[Ramadan]], along with celebrating his goals by performing the [[Sujud]].<ref name=\"themag\">{{cite news |last=Smithfield|first=Jackie|url=http://www.themag.co.uk/guest-writers/ramadan-a-positive-for-cisse-ba/|title=Ramadan A Positive For Cisse and Ba?|publisher= Dadyal Online |date=24 July 2012|accessdate=30 December 2012}}</ref> On 26 June 2017, Ba co-founded with [[Eden Hazard]], [[Yohan Cabaye]] and [[Moussa Sow]], an expansion [[North American Soccer League]] franchise, [[San Diego 1904 FC]], to begin playing in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.nasl.com/news/2017/06/26/nasl-announces-expansion-club-in-san-diego-for-2018-season |title = NASL announces expansion club in San Diego for 2018 season |publisher= North American Soccer League |date = 26 June 2017 |accessdate =26 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|15 March 2020}}<ref name=\"Soccerway\">{{cite web | url = https://int.soccerway.com/players/demba-ba/13192/ | title = D. Ba | publisher = Soccerway | accessdate = 6 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season !! Club !! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n! colspan=3 | France\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Coupe de France|Coupe France]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|2005\u201306|||[[FC Rouen|Rouen]]|||[[Championnat de France amateur|CFA]]||26||22||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||22\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | France total\n!26||22||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||22\n|-\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Belgium\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Belgian Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Belgian First Division|2006\u201307]]|||[[R.E. Mouscron|Mouscron]]|||[[Belgian Pro League|Pro League]]||12||8||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12